<head>
<title>NEWSLETTER Vol 1, No.1: May 1996</title>
<body  background="../pics/back4.gif" text="#661621">

<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign="top">
<a href="../about/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/about.gif"  alt="[About]" vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../family/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/family2.gif" alt="[Family]"  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../health/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/health2.gif" alt="[Health]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../work/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/work2.gif alt="[Work]" hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../mailcprn.htm">
<img src="../pics/feedbac2.gif" alt="[Feedback]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href="../search.htm"-->
<!--img src="../pics/search2.gif" alt="[Search]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><b>CPRN Newsletter No. 1</b><br>
<i>May, 1996</i><p></center>
<a name="top_page">Welcome</a> to the first CPRN Newsletter.  CPRN was founded in December, 1994, by Judith Maxwell, with financial support from six federal agencies.  In the past year, we have created a "virtual" institute, composed of three Networks of researchers, focused on Family, Work, and Health.  All three Networks are now running flat out to deliver a vibrant research agenda, with the help of first class researchers across the country.  This Newsletter will be published twice a year to update colleagues, funders and other stakeholders, as well as the Canadian public, about our many activities.<p>

<center><h3>Background on CPRN</h3></center>

The mission of CPRN is to create knowledge and lead public debate on social and economic issues important to the well-being of Canadians, in order to help build a more just, prosperous and caring society.  
<p>
Activities are organized through Networks which tap the skills of researchers in universities and think tanks across the country.  They are connected by CPRN to key stakeholders in the field of research -- provincial and federal policy-makers, experts in the private and 
nonprofit sectors, and providers and workers at the community level.  
<p>
The stakeholders help to define the research agenda, monitor the progress of the work, and interpret the results. They also provide funding and in-kind support. The research has a strong policy focus.  It is original, often pioneering, work, which crosses the boundaries of disciplines, jurisdictions, and institutions. 
<p>
The first publication, from the Family Network, is Exploring Canadian Values, by Suzanne Peters.  It reports on the results of pioneering work with public dialogue --helping citizens to go beyond top-of-the-mind opinions to more considered public judgment -- on their deepest social values.  That work is being used to anchor current debate on the remaking of the social safety net, as the federal government cuts back on transfers to provinces, and helps to inform the discussion on national identity.  For a list of CPRN publications, see <a href="#publctns">Publications and Speeches</a>.

<center><h3>What's New?</h3></center>

<b><i>The Social Union</i></b><p>
The social union is the web of citizen rights and obligations that give effect to our shared sense of social purpose and common citizenship.  A Roundtable in early March created a neutral space for provincial, federal and other experts to explore the future of the social union and its connections to social policy reform, federalism, and citizenship.  Margaret Biggs, Research Fellow in the Family Network, prepared case studies in education, internal trade and social programs.  These assessments centred on the implications for intergovernmental cooperation and problem-solving, transparency and openness to citizens , and ongoing policy renewal.  Participants had a candid discussion of the fabric and significance of the "social union" and the relative roles and 
responsibilities of different levels of government and citizens.
<p>
A Working Paper building on the day's discussions, drawing lessons from other countries' experiences, and reporting the case studies will be published in early summer. <p>

<b><i>The Future of Work</i></b><p>
A Workshop in late April sponsored by Industry Canada encouraged brainstorming about future scenarios for work.  With these scenarios in hand, participants from provinces, federal agencies, private and nonprofit organizations mapped an array of policy responses.  Gordon Betcherman, Director of the Work Network, and Kathryn McMullen will write a synthesis of the background research and the day's proceedings.
<p>
<a name="society"><b><i>The Society We Want</i></b><p>
The Family Network, directed by Suzanne Peters, has launched a project to permit citizens to work through their values and preferences with respect to the reform of social programs.   The discussion groups will be organized by 12 national partners, which are listed on <a href="#partners">New Partners in The Society We Want</a>. The Network convened five sessions 
(in Vancouver, Winnipeg, Toronto, Montreal, and Halifax) to orient local partners to the public dialogue process.  They will use  a dialogue kit prepared by the Family Network, based on models developed by the Kettering Foundation and others in the United States as a means to develop democratic engagement.  
<p>
Citizens have the opportunity to meet in a neutral space to explore one of five issues central to The Society We Want: Our Children, Health, Work, the Social Safety Net, and the Role of Government.  Each group completes a feedback sheet, which will be analysed by CPRN and archived at Carleton University.  Feedback includes the benchmarks that group members have identified as an indicator of progress toward the society they want.  About 250 discussion groups are expected to take place by the end of June, when a Newsletter will bring participants and policy makers up to date.  Looking longer term, CPRN is currently fund-raising to extend and deepen the dialogue and communicate the results.
<p>
<i><b>Health Network Strategic Plan</i></b><p>
The Steering Committee for the Health Network reviewed a strategic plan for research in January, helping CPRN to set research priorities among a large number of possible projects.  The program, under the leadership of Network Director, Marcus Hollander, is pursuing two main themes.  One is the organization and management of health services, where a number of projects are now under way.  The second theme will be pursued in the next year -- creating the capacity to do policy research related to population 
health.  With ready access to the work of the Family and Work Networks, the Health Network is ideally placed to explore the challenging issues facing governments as they begin to treat health as a cross-cutting issue of relevance to many ministries/departments.
<p>
<i><b>Social Cohesion</i></b><p>
"We are beginning to understand that our capacity to generate wealth depends critically on the quality of social interaction -- the trust and reciprocity that are woven into the social fabric. . . . . How does a country build social cohesion at a time when economic pressures are creating fault lines that divide generations, communities, and regions?" [CPRN Annual Report, 1994-95]   These are the overarching issues which drive CPRN's research agenda.  Judith Maxwell has been pursuing them in a paper on the Social Dimensions of Economic Growth [1996 Hanson Lecture], with public speeches on corporate social responsibility and on community 
responsibility.  Copies are available via the CPRN Home Page or on request.  These issues often spillover into the debate on national unity -- where Judith Maxwell has been advising a number of groups and organizations. <p>

<b><i>Non-profit Sector</i></b><p>
Nonprofits, and especially the voluntary sector, are a key foundation for civil society.  All are under stress these days, as governments cut their funding, on the one hand, and transfer more responsibilities on the other.   This project, funded by the Kahanoff Foundation and directed for CPRN by Ron Hirshhorn, <a href="mailto:rhirsh@magi.com">rhirsh@magi.com</a>, will create a portrait of the economic and social role of this sector and undertake indepth studies of the tax and legal frameworks in which it operates.  The Advisory Committee will be reviewing first drafts of the studies  in June, and preliminary results will be examined at a Roundtable of people from the sector in September.  The project is to be completed by the end of 1996.
<p>
<b><i>Home Page</i></b><p>
Visit our Home Page at http://www.cprn.com  You will find this Newsletter there, along with lots of other useful information about the 
research program and publications. <p>
<center><h3>New Projects Under Development</h3></center>

<i><b>Work In The Public Sector</b></i><p>
Gordon Betcherman, Director of the Work Network, and Anil Verma from the University of Toronto have completed a feasibility study for a research project on Human Resources in Government. Studies will include: the public sector labour market; the changing nature of government activity, workforce renewal, and the transformation of the workplace.  The research design will be tested at a workshop this summer, and work will be launched as soon as funding is in place. <p>

<b><i>HIV/AIDS Prevention</i></b><p>
A workshop in March produced valuable input for a strategic plan for economic research on HIV/AIDS prevention (to be sponsored by Health Canada).  The workshop expressed support for building capacity to do this kind of research in Canada, for developing appropriate outcome measures, and for creating a framework for economic analysis for HIV/AIDS prevention.  Interest was also expressed in determining the role economic analysis can play in policy decisions.  The strategic plan will be submitted to Health Canada.
<p>
<b><i>Benchmark Costs for Health Care</i></b><p>
With the trend toward shifting patients from institutional to community based care, health care managers (and policy makers) need reliable benchmarks for the cost of institutional and home care for patients with similar care requirements.  In partnership with the Canadian Association for Community Care, the Health Network is completing the methodological work required to collect reliable cost data from patients and institutions.  The focus is on children with special care needs and seniors.  Funding for this stage of the work has been provided by Health Canada.
<p>
Apart from creating badly needed benchmarks to guide the placement of patients, the studies will also provide valuable insights into the amount of informal care provided by family and friends, and will give some guidance about the share of the total cost covered by public and private funding.  
<p>
<b><i>Families and Labour Market Dynamics</i></b><p>
The Family Network is examining the well-being of families from four angles: their poverty and composite incomes, their ability to cope with the changing labour market, their responses to special care-giving needs, and their investments in children.  
<p>
These papers form the first stage of a longer-range research program on the Social and Economic Dynamics of  Families to explore how Canadian families cope with the difficulties imposed by the changing social, economic, and policy environment. In examining family dynamics, the Network wants to know what happens inside families and across families: how time is allocated, how income is shared, how responsibilities are distributed, and how sacrifices/investments are made.  
<p>
For more information, request CPRN's Family Network Newsletter or see our home page at: http://www.cprn.com .

<center><h3>Some New CPRN Players</h3></center>
CPRN works because so many Canadians are prepared to invest their time and energy in Network events -- as advisers on research, as participants in workshops and roundtables, doing peer review and so on. These volunteers enrich our work immensely.  We wish to acknowledge and thank the following people who have recently agreed to participate in the Networks.
<p>
<b><i>New Sponsors</i></b><p>
The
 Royal Bank of Canada has signed up to be the first corporate Sponsor of CPRN, with a three year financial contribution.  Other new supporters include IPSCO, NOVA and Power Corp.  Thank you!  
<p>
<b><i>New Research Fellows</i></b><p>
Two Research Fellows have joined the Family Network for the current year.  David Cheal, a professor of sociology at the University of 
Winnipeg, is actively involved in the Network's research on the Social and Economic Dynamics of Families -- with a special focus on the extent to which "family income" really reflects the well-being of individual family members.  A distinguished academic, David will be publishing a thoughtful book entitled New Poverty about mid-year.
<p>
Margaret Biggs, a policy analyst with extensive experience in Ottawa, has spearheaded the work on Governance and Accountability in the Social Union.  Both are enriching our lives and producing good work.
<p>

