<head>
<title>CPRN Annual Report - Health Network </title>
<body  background="../pics/back4.gif" text="#661621">
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign="top">
<a href="../about/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/about.gif"  alt="[About]" vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../family/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/family2.gif" alt="[Family]"  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../health/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/health2.gif" alt="[Health]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../work/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/work2.gif" alt="[Work]" hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../mailcprn.htm">
<img src="../pics/feedbac2.gif" alt="[Feedback]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href="../search.htm"-->
<!--img src="../pics/search2.gif" alt="[Search]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name="top_page"><H2>CPRN Annual Report - 1995-96</a><BR>
Health Network<BR>
Marcus Hollander<BR>
(Victoria, B.C.)
</h2>
</center>
<P>
The Health Network is spearheading research on health services and population health.  Both are important to the sustainability of the health system in the longer term.</P>
<P>
In its first year, the Health Network has focused its energy on creating knowledge about community-based health care -- the new focus of health care delivery in Canada.  In the year ahead, it will launch new projects exploring the policy dimensions of the social and economic determinants of health -- known as population health.  To support this work, the Network has a talented group of associates across Canada with diverse experience and training (Appendix A).</P>
<P>
<Strong>Health Services</strong></P>
<P>
This theme area includes a number of projects focused on high profile policy problems. The trend to moving chronically ill individuals out of large institutions and into community based care has highlighted the need for information on the relative cost-effectiveness of care in the community.  And concern about the spread of HIV/AIDS creates a need for economic research on both the care and treatment and the prevention of this epidemic.  More generally, there is a need for better decision-making tools.</P>
<P>
<STRONG><I>Community-based Care</I></STRONG></P>
<P>
One of the missing elements in health care research is accurate benchmark costs to support decisions about where to place individuals with given care requirements.  In cooperation with the Canadian Association for Community Care, the Health Network is developing the detailed design for measuring the cost-effectiveness of home care services compared for seniors and for children with special needs to care in an institution.  In addition, the Network has developed an inventory of services for these children for each province and territory.  The next stages of the work will involve a) pilot studies, followed by b) field work to collect data from individuals with comparable care needs. Once the data are collected, the analysis will produce valuable insights about the role of the informal caregiver and the private costs of community care.</P>
<P>
<STRONG><I>HIV/AIDS</I></STRONG></P>
<P>
In an effort to build greater capacity for economic research on this epidemic, Health Canada has asked CPRN to coordinate the selection process and monitoring for six large scale research projects (listed in Appendixf B).  The Health Network conducts site visits, organizes workshops which permit the six teams to learn from each other, and will publish a synthesis of the results in early 1998.</P>
<P>
The Health Network has also been asked by Health Canada to organize economic research on the prevention of HIV/AIDS.  A national workshop in Vancouver in March identified a need for active participation by community-based representatives.  As a result, a second workshop was held in September to get reaction from people with front-line service experience to a draft discussion paper and to set research priorities.</P>
<P>
<STRONG><I>Health Care Decision-Making</I></STRONG></P>
<P>
The growing complexity of clinical and policy decisions in health care has led to a search for new technologies to support decision-making.  The Health Network has challenged the hyperbole about the use of Decision Support Tools, in a study commissioned by the National Forum on Health.  It shows there is much more scope for using these tools in clinical settings than in the more complex and value-laden work of managers and policy makers.</P>
<P>
The Ontario Ministry of Health has commissioned the Health Network to examine the strengths and weaknesses of existing models of  resource allocation in 1996-97.  The study will provide a comparative analysis of techniques for allocating funds in the health sector.</P>
<P>
As health care systems across Canada transform, there is a need for continuous policy learning.  Policy makers need to track changes in policy and programs in other jurisdictions and to assess best practices.  With funding from the Max Bell Foundation, the Health Network will conduct a feasibility study for a national clearing house on health policy and program innovations.</P>
<P>
<Strong>Population Health</strong></P>
<P>
Health, in the sense of wellness, is, or should be, the objective of most government departments, including justice, environment, housing, labour, social services, and so on.  The Max Bell Foundation has provided seed money to the Health Network to launch a program of studies on the policy dimensions of population health. A feasibility study is now underway, led by Jan Skirrow, a Network Associate.</P>
<P>
In March, an exploratory workshop on Employment and Health, in partnership with the Institute for Work and Health, highlighted two essential dimensions to incorporate into the framework for population health -- values and time.  These findings highlight the linkages to other CPRN Networks -- specifically, to the Work Network essay on the Future of Work, and to the Family Network research on the core social values of Canadians, as well as the ongoing study of how families allocate money and time.</P>
<P>
As the Population Health program gets underway, we expect to launch cross-Network projects which will build on the expertise and contacts of all three Networks.   A first step in that direction will be exploratory work on social capital -- mapping the existing knowledge base, building a network of interested researchers, and agreeing on a common conceptual framework.</P>
<HR>
