<html>
<head>
<title>CPRN Annual Report - Work Network </title>
<body  background="../pics/back4.gif" text="#661621">
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign="top">
<a href="../about/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/about.gif"  alt="[About]" vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../family/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/family2.gif" alt="[Family]"  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../health/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/health2.gif" alt="[Health]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../work/index.htm">
<img src="../pics/work2.gif" alt="[Work]" hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../mailcprn.htm">
<img src="../pics/feedbac2.gif" alt="[Feedback]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href="../search.htm"-->
<!--img src="../pics/search2.gif" alt="[Search]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center>
<h2><a name="top_page">CPRN Annual Report - 1995-96</a><BR>
Work Network<BR>
Gordon Betcherman<BR>
(Ottawa, Ontario)
</h2>
</center>
<P>
The Work Network strives to consider the "cutting edge" issues in the world of work -- unemployment and job creation, earnings levels and their distribution, the growth of nonstandard work, new skill needs and their implications for education and training, workplace innovation, the role of unions, and so on.  These issues are all part of the transformation from an industrial to post-industrial society.</P>
<P>
Highlights in the coming year will include the release of the research and policy reports from the Employment and Training Project; the publication of a far-reaching essay on the Future of Work; the launch of a major project on Human Resources in Government; and the development of a new study on Globalization and the Labour Market.</P>
<P>
<Strong>Employment and Training</strong></P>
<P>
Since the start-up of the Work Network in 1994, the core activity has been a large-scale project on employment and training.  Two questions have been at the heart of this work: "Training for what?" and "What kinds of training work and for whom?"  The project included a number of research components addressing the changing job structure, the impacts of technological change on work and training, youth employment, and training.  The centrepiece of the project was a national study on workplace training undertaken by Ekos Research Associates.  Funding for the Employment and Training Project was provided by Human Resources Development Canada, the Canadian Labour Force Development Board, the New Brunswick  Labour Force Development Board, and the provincial governments in Ontario, British Columbia, and Saskatchewan.</P>
<P>
The synthesis report, Training in the New Economy (to be published in late 1996), concludes that our existing institutions and practices are not sufficient to meet the skill demands of the new economy.  The up-skilling of the job structure, shifting lifecycle patterns, and changing employment arrangements demand an education and training system that is much more forward-looking, flexible, and that truly supports lifelong learning.  The current system seems to serve the needs of people who already have substantial human capital, but it does not respond to the requirements of people on the margins of the formal economy, in nonstandard jobs, or employed in small, traditionally managed firms.  As currently structured, education and training in Canada actually reinforce the trend toward social exclusion and the polarization of income.</P>
<P>
<HR width=75%>
<P>
<Strong>Forthcoming Employment and Training Publications</strong></P>
<P>
Gordon Betcherman, <I>Training for the New Economy</I> (synthesis report)</P>
<P>
Kathryn McMullen, <I>Skill and Employment Effects of Computer-Based Technology</I>: The Results of the Working With Technology Survey III" (study).</P>
<P>
Gordon Betcherman, Norm Leckie, and Kathryn McMullen, <I>Developing Skills in the Canadian Workplace: The Results of the Ekos Workplace Training Survey</I> (study)</P>
<P>
Richard Marquardt, <I>Youth Transitions</I> (working paper)</P>
<P>
William Coffey, <I>Employment Growth and Change in the Canadian Urban System</I> (working paper)</P>
<P>
Gordon Betcherman and Norm Leckie, <I>Youth Employment Trends</I> (working paper)<BR>
<P>
<HR width=75%>
<P>
<Strong>The Future of Work</strong></P>
<P>
In April 1996, the Work Network hosted a roundtable in Ottawa where about 30 experts met to discuss emerging trends in the nature of work and employment and to debate potential policy responses.  Building on that discussion, Gordon Betcherman and Graham Lowe (University of Alberta) are writing an essay on the Future of Work.  To be released in late 1996, the study is rooted in the Canadian experience and focuses on the choices Canadians face in adapting their thinking and their behaviour to this new environment.  The Future of Work Project is being financed by Industry Canada with a contribution from Noranda Inc.</P>
<P>
<Strong>Human Resource Issues in Government</strong></P>
<P>
There are compelling pressures on all governments to rethink their human resource strategies, as they change the role of government and the way they do their business.  The Human Resource Issues in Government project will help government decision-makers to redefine the strategies, policies, and procedures needed to develop  more flexible, efficient, and innovative workplaces and to foster a healthy, motivated, and skilled workforce.  The proposed studies are built around three questions:</P>
<OL type="1"><P>
<LI>What will be the future skill requirements of governments and how can these be met?</P>
<P>
<LI>What public-sector workplace models can meet the emerging demands for knowledge, service, and efficiency and how can these be achieved?</P>
<P>
<LI>How can the public-sector labour market adjust to the simultaneous challenges of downsizing and workforce  renewal?</P></OL>
<P>
A detailed research design, prepared by Gordon Betcherman along with Anil Verma from the University of Toronto is now out for discussion and in search of funding.  A workshop to finalize the research program is planned for November 1996.</P>
<P>
<Strong>Globalization and the Labour Market</strong></P>
<P>
The impact of globalization of product markets on employment is often debated.  Views range from near apocalyptic visions of job loss and a "race to the bottom" to favorable prospects for wage increases and an up-skilling of work.  Unfortunately, serious analysis of the labour market effects of globalization is scarce.  In coming months, the Work Network will begin to develop a research agenda which will a) analyze the labour market impacts,  and b) explore how countries are adapting institutions and regulations.</P>
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href="#top_page">click here</a>.
<P>
Annual Report <a href=anncont.htm>Table of Contents</a>
</td></tr>
