</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title> </title>
<body  background="../pics/back4.gif" text="#661621">

<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign="top">
<a href="../about/index.html">
<img src="../pics/about.gif"  alt="[About]" vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../work/index.html">
<img src="../pics/work2.gif" alt="[Work]"  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../health/index.html">
<img src="../pics/health2.gif" alt="[Health]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href="../mailcprn.html">
<img src="../pics/feedbac2.gif" alt="[Feedback]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--<a href="../search.html">-->
<!--<img src="../pics/search2.gif" alt="[Search]"   hspace=20 width=70 border=0
></a><br>-->

</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
                     
<em><h3><a name="1">Stage 1:</a>  Conceptual Papers and Feasibility Work to Frame
Future Empirical Projects</h3></em>  
<P>
June 1995  Dec 1996
<P>
<em>A. The policy context and methodological issues</em>
<P>
These papers are intended to set the stage for policy research
related to families in Canada.
<P>
These include:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>
a catalogue of public policy innovations related to families
that have arisen or are likely to arise from changing policy context,
including withdrawal of direct federal activity in social policy
area, provincial initiatives toward disentanglement, and responses
at municipal and community levels. 
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>
a discussion of how to evaluate the effects of changing and
comparative public programs on different choices made by families,
in particular a consideration of the usefulness of different approaches,
including experimental models (e.g., putting people into two treatment
groups) versus the use of existing data sets to answer comparative
policy questions.  The latter discussion will include consideration
of the limitations of current data sets related to factors such
as sample sizes insufficient to capture stratified family differences,
provincial and municipal differences in benefit access, and other
issues.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>

These papers are intended to:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>
inform and orient researchers to possible projects of interest
by creating a central monitoring capacity to keep abreast of rapidly
changing policy developments. 
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td><td>
provide provincial and federal agencies with a basis to consider
opportunities for jointly funding policy research, both in order
to realize economies of scale and to create a shared information
base which may potentially influence the handling of policy and
political issues.
</td>
</tr>
<p>
<tr>
<Td valign=top>
c)</td>
<td>identify critical methodological issues and provide a common
foundation for addressing them.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<em>B.  Families' transactions and adaptations</em>
<P>
These papers are intended to build a conceptual framework on transactions
undertaken by families within and across households which can
support policy relevant research.  Transactions are defined as
the transfer of resources that may have an impact on the ability
of families as a whole or individuals in families to successfully
adapt to environmental changes.
<P>
Building on an initial conceptual paper supported by Human Resources
Development Canada, these papers will explore how the transactions
framework can help to inform policy focused research on adaptations
in Canadian families resulting from changing social trends, economic
restructuring, and in response to government policies.
<P>
Topics may include transactions under the broad domains of:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>family financial organization, with a focus on income distributions
and pooling within households, including coping low wage and sole
support families; inter-generational equity; payments from non-custodial
to custodial households; financial management in circumstances
of unemployment and contingent work, and other issues,
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>physical assistance provided within and across families, with
a focus on child care and child development, division of household
work, elder care, and other issues,
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>social and emotional support family members offer to one another
which, while related to finances and time, cannot be reduced to
these per se, with a focus on caring work across and within generations
which establishes children's best interests. maintains family
resiliency, and reduces the demand for state supports,
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>advice, management, and assistance in organization and decision making,
with a focus on those supports which families accomplish with
and without state intervention, including support to sole support
mothers and other vulnerable families,
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>5)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>biological transfers, including sexuality, procreation, reproductive
technologies, blood and organ transplants and others.  While these
transactions may not appear to have immediate relevance to the
social policy arena, they help to broaden the conceptualization
of transactions, with relevance to family legal policy in the
areas of custody, new reproductive technologies, and biological
human rights.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
These papers are intended to:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>a.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>lay the foundation for an empirical definition of families
by identifying those activities and transactions which families
undertake, and the key factors and conditions shaping them which
will require further study.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>b.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>suggest the ways in which these private, nonmarket transactions
may underpin labour market and voluntary sector participation.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>c.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>suggest avenues through which the Network can exploit existing,
newly available, or original data sets to study factors in families'
resiliency, including quantitative and qualitative strategies,
options for linking subsets of observations across several surveys
based on single sample frames or linked questions, and clear outcome
measures.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>d.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>identify gaps in data collection related to the conceptual
issues identified and potential mechanisms for addressing them.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>e.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>be capable of integration to support a broad theoretical and
methodological overview for future research on family transactions,
in particular to inform decisions related to data collation and
collection envisioned in Stage 2 below. 
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>f.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>identify project priorities to be undertaken by the Network
in the current policy context with regard to family transactions.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<P>

<em><h3><a name="2">Stage 2:</a>  Initial Data Collation and Collection on Families'
Transactions</h3></em>
<P>
January 1995  December 1996
<P>
Stage 1 is likely to identify potential data sources and critical
data gaps which will need to be filled.  In order to stimulate
an empirical definition of families in Canada, the Network will
work with partners such as Statistics Canada and other interested
agencies, to collate existing data from related surveys and to
collect new supplementary data.
<P>
Identification of data from existing surveys relevant to a transactions
approach could involve an inventory or catalogue of relevant data
items in both cross-sectional and new longitudinal surveys.  The
Survey of Income and Labour Dynamics (SLID), the National Longitudinal
Survey of Children (NLSC), and the National Population Health
Survey (NPHS) are important new data sources as the agenda unfolds.
 SLID will offer important information on changing labour market
and income issues for families, and the NLSC and NPHS address
family context and characteristics in relation to outcome measures
of individual health and well-being.
<P>
Options for collection of new data could include: a) a coordinated
case study snowball sample of a small number of families in several
provinces in which in depth interviews will be conducted with
all family members, b) a one-off survey of key family transactions
in Canada, and/or c) a strategy to link the case studies, the
one-off survey or both to an existing survey by sampling members
of the survey population.
<P>
These data collation and collection activities will be designed
to create the profile of those transactions typical across families
of different structures and cultures. Data collection would be
designed to stratify across populations in sufficient sample size
to enable researchers to look at family issues and family structures
of interest (e.g., lone parents, blended families, or other characteristics).
 Consideration will also need to be given to variations in access
across the population, including ethnic groups and more vulnerable
families.  The resulting data will built an empirical foundation
for definitions of families relevant to different policy contexts
as well as a benchmark for future studies for families' transactions.
<P>
On the basis of this survey and other collated information, the
Network will want to consider the potential for developing a simulation
model of families' transactions which synthesizes available information
from existing databases, information from a one-off survey, and
the results of a coordinated set of case studies.
<P>
<p>

<h3><a name="3">Stage 3:</a>  Selection and Implementation of 
Research Projects within the Three Key Themes</h3>
<P>
June 1996  December 1998
<P>
Once the data have been assembled, proposals for specific empirical
projects will be solicited to address specific policy focused
questions within each theme area.  Some examples of potential
projects are illustrated for each theme.
<P>
<em>Theme One: Families' Restructuring</em>
<P>
What are the benchmarks of resilient families? <br>
What are the benchmarks of vulnerable families in Canada?  
<P>
How do these benchmarks vary in families of different cultural,
racial, life course stage, geographic, and other characteristics?
<P>
What are the trends in families' formation, cohabitation, dissolution,
sole parenthood, blended families, custody and access, child support,
child care arrangements, division of labour vis-à-vis labour market
participation, elderly care, and other restructuring trends in
Canada?
<P>
What is the pattern of inter-generational support in families in
Canada?  How does it affect inter-generational equity and well-being?
 
<P>
Project examples: 
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Review of the changing adaptations of sole support families,
including the factors which induce change and the role of non-custodial
fathers and other non-household kin in supporting these families.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Comparison of transactions in families with similar socio-economic
characteristics in order to understand the impacts on different
child outcomes.  This could include comparison of the pattern
of inter-familial and inter-household support afforded to sole parent
employed and unemployed families in relation to cognitive and
emotional outcomes for children.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Comparison of family coping strategies in given changing age
and health patterns.  This could include research on the cohabitation
patterns of Canadians of the youngest and oldest adult cohorts,
including renewed supports provided in families of different income
quintiles.  This could include research on the ways in which families
of middle age and middle income will adapt to increased support
pressures from elder and younger family members, including parents
and adult children who may be disadvantaged in labour market restructuring.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>1.5&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Other factors in the changing social, cultural, and physical
environments of families which may affect coping strategies and
adaptations, as well as the study of reciprocal impacts.  For
example, family stress may lessen capacity to engage in environmentally
safe behaviour, jeopardizing the well-being of family members
while in turn heightening environment hazard.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<em>Theme Two: Economic Restructuring</em>
<P>
What are the impacts of insecure or contingent work on families?<br>

What are the impacts of unemployment? What has been the impact
of job polarization on the opportunities afforded different families?
<P>
How do these economic changes affect families' structures, cultures
and transactions within and across households?  What are the successful
coping strategies of families faced with difficulties?  What have
been the responses of families faced with new opportunities? What
are the characteristics of families' resiliency in each case?
What are the responses of different family members?
<P>
Which families use contingent or nonstandard jobs as a lever for
a certain part of their life and move on? Which families get stuck
in these types of jobs?
<P>
Do different kinds of families make different kinds of decisions
or investments? 
<P>
What have been the impacts on different kinds of families, including
younger families, and other marginalized groups?  How has mobility
in families been affected as a result of labour market changes?
 How do these changes affect different members particularly with
regard to the resources available to them and their allocation
of domestic work?
<P>
Possible Project Examples:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>2.1&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>The changing impacts of labour market polarization and destandardization
on families.  Research may be focused on the expenditure, consumption,
child care arrangements, and household division of labour in families
experiencing changed labour market experiences, especially unemployment
and increased part-time work, in contrast to families with no
employment changes.  Similarly, the adaptations of different families
to decreased income in the face of labour market changes, including
resort to the underground economy, assistance from kin and non-kin
networks, and other coping strategies.
<P>
The Network would be interested both in data on how the activities/transactions
of different families change with unemployment and on the impact
that these transactions have for different family members, especially
children.  While SLID data will offer increased understanding
of changes in employment patterns, the Network is concerned with
an additional challenge involved in exploring the impacts of these
changes on the kinds of issues currently studied in the Survey
of Consumer Finances, Survey of Family Expenditures, and General
Social Survey of Time Use.  These include issues related to how
families allocate time and resources as income diminishes.  Developing
studies which link these different data sources is a primary interest
of the Network.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Without changes in labour market status, the changes of diminished
real income.  This includes the kinds of investments families
make in financial and human terms, the ways in which long-term
provisioning for retirement and inheritance are organized in different
families.  This includes studies not only of earnings gaps, but
of total income and pension gaps among different members.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>2.3&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Study of families which move from social assistance to employment.
 One particular focus might be on lone parent families joining
the labour market to observe how they organize child care and
other elements of family life while giving up benefits normally
afforded with state assistance.  The successful and unsuccessful
trajectories of sole support parents upon labour market entry
would be of particular interest, in order to understand those
factors which appear to contribute to adaptation toward self-reliance.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>

<em>Theme Three:  Public Policies</em>
<P>
To what degree do particular public policies help or hinder that
successful adaptation?  How do public policy investments enhance
families' resiliency, responsiveness and capacity of families
to invest?  What are the barriers in policies? What are the buffers?
 Do barriers and buffers affect different families or different
family members differently?
<P>
How is the devolution of services from federal to provincial or
lower jurisdictions affecting family coping strategies? Have new
stresses been placed on families?
<P>
Does a balance of policy instruments offer better support for
families than a single policy incentive such as a work incentive?
 This research is intended to place the situation of families
in a broader policy context, in particular in the context of 
interactions between different programs and policies.
<P>
Project examples:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>The impacts of changing supports offered to families in different
provinces on transactions within and across families.  In particular,
assessments of the impacts of devolution of services to more community-based
mechanisms on families, including home care services for the elderly,
child care, and other policy areas.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>3.2&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>The impacts of different definitions of poverty, and policies
intended to remediate the negative impacts of poverty, including
government transfers such as unemployment insurance, welfare,
and taxation, on agreements around child support, and on the coping
strategies and transactions within and among custodial and non-custodial
households.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<Tr>
<td valign=top>3.3&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>The impacts of different social assistance regimes on youth,
both in terms of family involvement and educational aspirations
and attainment.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>3.4&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>The impact of changes in child support policy guidelines and
taxation on the custody, access, and child support arrangements
in families at different income quintiles.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>3.5&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Other family-related policy studies, including the effects
of social policy investments in communities, housing, transportation,
family law, family violence, and other program and policy impacts.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<p>

<h3><a name="4">Stage 4:</a> Address the macro context</h3> 
<P>
June 1998  December 1999
<P>

Research proposals will be requested which explore the comparative
economic and policy context of Canada and other jurisdictions,
including differences in unemployment rates, mobility, inter-generational
equity, families' structures and cultures, and other issues which
can shape outcomes and policy decisions.
<P>
With respect to an overview of the role of families in Canadian
society, the Network will request proposals for projects which
explore families' impacts on social well-being and broader cohesion,
measured socially and economically.  These projects may take up
issues related to families' transactions as part of the broad
institutional structure of Canadian society, including the ways
in which families may be the springboard for democratization or
authoritarianism.  This could include projects on the social and
economic costs of child care and socialization, care of dependent
adults, care of medically fragile children, providing homes to
extended family, and other areas.
<P>
Possible Project Examples
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>4.1&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Research on whether general governmental environmental supports
which affect families in the areas of health, employment, education,
etc. are more or less effective than specific policy interventions.
 This can be compared both for families on the whole and for particular
kinds of families.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>4.2&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Research on the impacts of policy approaches to supporting
families, including an examination of policies affecting general
public attitudes to families as a broad priority on the resiliency
and adaptation in families of diverse structures and cultures.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<em>Project Selection and Direction</em>
<P>
In order to benefit from economies of scale in the development
of new data, and to strengthen explanatory power through insights
from many disciplines, the Network wishes to create consortiums
focused on a shared research agenda. For these reasons, proposals
from research partnerships will be strongly encouraged and linkages
among policy makers will be fostered.
<P>
Proposals are anticipated which range between several months to
three years in length, with funds to vary accordingly.  Studies
are expected which rely on both surveys and on in-depth qualitative
research.  The Network will not consider proposals for seed funding,
since projects are anticipated to flow from the preliminary conceptual
and empirical foundation laid by the Network.
<P>
Proposals will be selected with the advice of the Steering Committee
of the Family Network according to the following criteria:
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>a.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Relevance to important contemporary social, economic, and policy
issues.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>b.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Degree to which the project reflects the Network's emphasis
on family strength and resiliency and the conceptual framework
developed on family transactions
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>c.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Ability to integrate issues within at least one, and possibly
two or more themes
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>d.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Ability to address issues for families as a whole as well as
identified sub-populations of families, including lone parents,
ethnic groups, income ranges, or others.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>e.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Originality of theory and/or data collection and or/research
methods, including multidisciplinarity.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>f.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Methodological feasibility, conciseness and rigour, including
a clear description of research steps, time frame, and budget
for each step.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>g.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Applicability to a comparative context across Canada to achieve
economies of scale.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>h.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Demonstrated agreement with relevant jurisdictions when a proposal
involves review of a policy or policies.
</td>
</tr>
<P>
<tr>
<td valign=top>g.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
<td>Demonstrated record of research and publication.</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
Project proposals will be subject to a peer review process.  Deadlines
will be tightly respected, including project progress reports
to be submitted for the approval of the Family Network Steering
Committee.  In long term projects, continued funding will be contingent
on the successful completion of each stage of work.
<P>
Research projects will be disseminated both through conferences
and through electronic publishing.  As the research agenda unfolds,
the Family Network proposes to create a synthesis of relevant
work.  The products will be the intellectual property of the CPRN.
 At the same time, authors will maintain publishing rights through
academic venues, including journal articles and monographs.
