<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>

<center><h3>	The Future of Work -- An Issues Paper<br>
	Gordon Betcherman and Kathryn McMullen<br>
	Canadian Policy Research Networks<br>	
	April 1996 </h3></center>


<b>Introduction</b>
<p>
	Over the past two decades, a number of important economic and 
labour market developments have occurred in Canada and other developed 
countries.  These include a slowdown in productivity growth; stagnant 
income growth and growing earnings inequality; increasing unemployment; 
and growing use of nonstandard employment forms.  At the same time, 
technological change, globalization, and other changes in economic, 
political, social, and demographic trends have contributed to a rapidly 
changing environment.  
<p>
	It is clear that the trends are not simply cyclical in nature; 
evidence suggests that there have been steady increases in most of them 
beginning in the 1970s and 80s.  What is less certain is whether the 
changes they represent are evolutionary in nature or whether they signal 
revolutionary changes in the socioeconomic structure of postindustrial 
economies.  While a fairly substantial literature has developed around 
these issues in the U.S. and Europe, they have received relatively little 
public debate in Canada.  
<p>
	Some observers of these trends, both in Canada and abroad, are 
now expressing concern over the costs of adjustment and over the possible 
future shape of the socioeconomic system.  Others are more optimistic, 
pointing to the new opportunities for industry growth and job creation 
that accompany changes in technology and the expansion of trading and 
investment opportunities.  While there is little consensus on the final 
outcomes of the current period of change, it is clear that there are a 
number of perspectives on both the nature of the problem and the 
appropriate public policy response.
<p>
	In the first part of this paper, we identify the key labour 
market trends that have sparked the debate over the future of work and 
briefly discuss some of the main causes of these trends.  The second part 
of the paper then summarizes the literature on the future of work, 
identifying three dominant points of view regarding the directions and 
implications of change.
<p>
<b>Trends in Work and Employment </b>
<p>
<i>Rising Unemployment</i>
<p>
	Through the post-war period, there has been a clear upward trend 
in unemployment in Canada, with the rate ratcheting up with each 
succeeding decade.  The 1980s in particular saw a large jump in the 
average unemployment rate, which rose to 9.4 per cent from 6.7 per cent 
for the 1970s.  Some observers have pointed to demographic changes, 
notably, steep rises in the labour force participation rates of women and 
youth, that took place over the period as an explanation for these 
increases.  But, analyses of the contribution of demographic factors to 
rising rates of unemployment have found their role to be partial, at 
best. 
<p>
	  Long-term unemployment rates have increased substantially as 
well, though not as much in Canada as in Europe.  In 1995, about 15 per 
cent of the unemployed remained so for at least a year; over 30 per cent 
were unemployed for 6 months or more.  The problem of long-term 
unemployment has become particularly serious for workers over 45 years of 
age and previously employed in declining sectors of the economy.
<p>
	A related issue concerns trends in youth employment.  Here the 
issue has as much to do with the quality of youth employment as with 
elevated rates of unemployment.  For many, the school-to-work transition 
period has become more protracted as this group is finding it 
increasingly difficult to secure and maintain "good" jobs.  
<p>
<i>Growing Nonstandard Employment</i>
<p>
	Another important trend is the steady rise in nonstandard 
employment, including part-time, short-term and contract work, 
own-account self-employment, and work within the temporary-help 
industry.  Recent evidence from Statistics Canada shows that, by 1994, 
nonstandard employment had risen to about one-third of all jobs, and was 
spreading from the social services, retail trade, and other consumer 
services industries to the goods sector and the rest of the service 
sector as well.   Rates are particularly high for youth and are higher 
for women than for men, though the male-female gap has been narrowing.
<p>
	Two factors explain the increase in nonstandard employment.  On 
the one hand, employers appear to be using nonstandard employment 
(sometimes with a small core group) both as a tool to increase 
flexibility and to reduce costs.  The involuntary nonstandard employment 
that results is a source of growing economic insecurity, arising from 
concerns about the adequacy of earnings, accessibility of nonwage 
benefits, job security, and opportunities for training and career 
advancement. On the other hand, most part-time work, at least, is still 
voluntary.  Some individuals prefer the flexibility offered by 
nonstandard work and those with the right skills and aptitudes can also 
realize substantial income gains through self-employment.  However, it 
has been argued that high unemployment itself is likely contributing to 
the supply of labour prepared to work in nonstandard employment, thus 
making it attractive for employers to structure labour demand towards 
nonstandard forms.  
<p>
<i>Skill Shifts</i>
<p>
	The evidence suggests that a shift is taking place in the nature 
of skill requirements toward managerial, professional, and technical 
occupations.  It also appears that a process of  "upskilling" is taking 
place, particularly in terms of "cognitive complexity".  Much of this 
upskilling appears to be associated with the introduction of 
computer-based technological change. However, it is also still the case 
that a large percentage of workers are employed in what are considered 
low-skilled jobs.
<p>
<i>Stagnating Earnings and Earnings Polarization</i>
<p>
	From the end of the Second World War until the mid-70s, average 
individual earnings in Canada increased while their distribution remained 
relatively stable.  However, over the past two decades, real earnings 
have stagnated and the distribution of earnings has become more unequal 
and polarized.  Until now, in Canada, the transfer system has been able 
to maintain stability in the distribution of total family income.  The 
big question is to what extent this stability can be maintained given the 
challenges to the safety net accompanying the current fiscal situation. 
<p>
	Trends in individual earnings show that earnings inequality has 
increased significantly for males, in large part as a result of a 
significant drop in the real and relative earnings of the bottom 50 per 
cent.  Parallel, though less dramatic, trends occurred in the 1980s for 
females working full-time, full-year; recent analysis of the trends for 
the 1990s, however, suggests that these trends may have reversed.
<p>
	A number of hypotheses have been put forward in the literature as 
explanations for rising earnings inequality.  One concerns the shift of 
employment away from manufacturing and toward a service sector polarized 
between a set of high-wage "knowledge jobs" and low-wage "personal 
service" jobs.  Another is that technological change has increased the 
demand for highly skilled workers, resulting in a widening wage gap 
between highly experienced/educated workers and low-skilled workers.   A 
third explanation focuses on an apparent linkage between earnings 
inequality and rising polarization in hours worked.  Analysis of trends 
in working time show that there has been a significant decrease in the 
proportion of both men and women working a standard work week of 35 to 40 
hours.  Moreover, most of this decrease appears to be due to an increase 
in the proportion of hours worked in jobs involving more than 40 hours 
per week.
<p>
<b>The Causes</b>
<p>
	Two interrelated forces -- globalization and advances in 
information and communication technology -- have been the key drivers of 
change in the structure of economies and the nature of employment.  A 
number of social changes have also played a part.  
<p>
<i>	Globalization</i>
<p>
	Globalization has many aspects.  It concerns growing 
international competition as trade and investment have become more 
liberalized and as many national economies have become deregulated.  It 
involves a broadening of the content of trade and foreign investment, 
increasingly including not just goods, but also services.  And it 
consists of very large increases in the volume and speed of international 
financial flows.  But the concern over globalization includes more 
fundamental shifts as well ¾- in the location of production, in the 
structure of employment both in the advanced economies and in the 
developing countries, and in the international distribution of income and 
wealth.  
<p>
	Global economic integration has been driven largely by several 
forces.  The first is institutional ¾- in particular, the negotiation of 
more liberal international trade agreements and domestic market 
deregulation.  The second force has been innovation in communication and 
information technologies.  These technologies have facilitated 
international transactions, especially with respect to capital flows, and 
have allowed many services to become "tradeable".  Third, in the advanced 
industrial economies, there is less emphasis on high-volume, standardized 
output and more on specialized, "niche" products and services; 
globalization has become necessary to provide a large enough market base 
to support innovation-based economies.
<p>
<i>Information and Communication Technologies</i>
<p>
	The impact of technological change on the economy in general, and 
on employment more specifically, goes beyond its role in facilitating 
globalization, however.  Since the 1970s, computer-based information and 
communication technologies have diffused throughout the economy.   As 
they have penetrated more deeply, these technologies have contributed to 
major changes in  the goods and services being produced, in the work 
process, in organizational structures, in labour and skill requirements, 
and even in the nature of the employment contract.  Organizational 
strategies and designs developed for mass-production technologies are 
being re-fitted so that the new technologies can be used most 
effectively.  Many observers have argued that the necessary changes 
include flatter hierarchies, decentralized decision-making, and flexible 
operational procedures.
<p>
<i>Social Changes</i>
<p>
	Huge changes have also taken place in the nature of the Canadian 
labour force.  It is now older, more highly educated, and more ethnically 
diverse than it was 20 years ago, and it includes a much higher 
proportion of women.  As a result, compared to a generation ago, many 
workers now have new and very different expectations and needs.  Probably 
the most important shift has been the increasing role of women in paid 
employment outside of the home which has created new pressures relating 
to the need to balance work and family responsibilities.
<p>
<b>Where Are We Headed? Three Scenarios</b>
<p>
	What does all of this imply for the future of work?  As a 
starting point, it seems plausible to assume that the future will not be 
like the past. One device for thinking about a future that is 
unpredictable is to construct scenarios, not necessarily to predict which 
is the "right" one, but rather to consider various possibilities and what 
each suggests about what we should be doing.  In this section, we provide 
a synthesis of the existing literature by presenting three scenarios on 
the future of work.
<p>
	During the 1990s, hosts of social scientists, business gurus, and 
others have speculated about where work is heading in the emerging world 
of global integration and technological revolution.  It should be noted 
that this is not the first time that the future of work has received such 
intense speculation -- it seems to occur every couple of decades or so.  
And, in fact, those familiar with earlier "future of work" debates will 
likely recognize many aspects of the current discussion.
<p>
	The scenarios we present below are based on a review covering a 
wide range of literature, spanning different disciplines, and including 
both academic and more popularized books and articles.  While there are 
obviously very serious issues in the newly industrialized and less 
developed countries, our focus here is on the advanced industrialized 
world.  The synthesis is largely based on American and, to a lesser 
degree, European studies.  There is very little written from a Canadian 
perspective, which raises an important question about the degree to which 
a debate largely framed outside this country needs to be modified to 
reflect the Canadian situation.
<p>
	Three scenarios are described below -- one is fundamentally 
pessimistic, another optimistic, and a third which we have labelled an 
"almost business as usual" scenario.  These differ in terms of their 
assessment of the magnitude and pace of environmental change, what the 
full impacts of this change will be, and what should be done in 
response.  Naturally, no typology is "neat" and there are likely to be 
disagreements about the number of categories and the boundaries 
separating them.  However, these scenarios offer a useful start for 
considering the core issues around the future of work.
<p>
<i>Qualified Pessimists</i>
<p>
	Like the others, the "qualified pessimist" scenario has a 
strongly-rooted historical tradition.  In the 1990s, its most popular 
articulation at least in North America has been Jeremy Rifkin's, The End 
of Work.  Other prominent examples include Global Dreams by Richard 
Barnet and John Cavanaugh and Paul Kennedy's Preparing for the 
Twenty-First Century.  While the essential picture is pessimistic, and in 
some variants even apocalyptic, we have included the qualifier in the 
label because writers in this vein do believe that the future may be 
salvageable but only with what amounts to revolutionary social change.  
We will get to this later in the paper.
<p>
	This scenario begins with the proposition that we are now going 
through the equivalent of another industrial revolution, fueled not by 
coal or oil but by information and communication technology.  The 
perspective on technology overwhelmingly emphasizes its potential for 
replacing people with machinery.  While recognizing that earlier waves of 
technological change have also had serious displacement impacts, the 
pessimistic scenario posits that the effects on workers this time are 
going to be particularly gruesome.
<p>
	There are essentially three reasons for this pessimism.  First, 
the potential for the new technologies to displace workers is 
extraordinary in that "mental" as well as "manual" labour is now at 
risk.  Second, while earlier waves of mechanization and automation drove 
people off the farms and out of the factories, there was always an 
emerging sector -- first manufacturing and then services -- to soak up 
the displaced.  This time, it is argued, there is no such sector in 
sight.  Finally, globalization is extending the power of capital beyond 
the reach of any balancing "social" forces including government 
regulation and collective bargaining -- forces that were designed to 
operate at the national level only.  In the pessimistic scenario, the 
central instrument of globalization is the multinational corporation that 
is increasingly stateless and footloose, surveying the globe for the most 
advantageous locations in which to settle.
<p>
	The crisis envisaged by the pessimistic scenario is primarily a 
distributional crisis.  Technology offers the potential for major gains 
in global aggregate wealth but, left alone, the market will concentrate 
that wealth in the rich countries, and in the hands of capital and an 
aristocracy of the highly-skilled.  Mass unemployment will result with 
acute income polarization.  For most workers, employment will be 
intermittent and contingent.  With production work either eliminated by 
technology or relocated to lower-cost sites, jobs in the advanced 
countries essentially will be limited to the service sector.
<p>
	The pessimistic scenario typically links this dismal employment 
and distributional picture to broader sociological and psychological 
consequences.  Marginalization and loss of identity are seen as likely 
for the large numbers without a stable role in the future economy.  And, 
as succeeding generations recognize their apparent futures, violence and 
crime can be expected.
<p>
<i>Qualified Optimists</i>
<p>
	The optimistic scenario actually shares the same starting point 
as the pessimists -- that we are now in the midst of another industrial 
revolution, a "postindustrial" revolution driven by information and 
communication technology and by globalization.  However, the implications 
drawn are diametrically opposed to those identified by the pessimists.  
The optimistic scenario is particularly prevalent in the business press 
with high-profile strategic consultants making the major contributions.  
Examples include Peter Drucker's many books and articles, Jobshift by 
William Bridges, and Charles Handy's The Age of Uncertainty.
<p>
	The argument at the centre of the optimistic scenario is that the 
technological progress and globalization driving the postindustrial 
revolution offer new momentum for social and economic opportunity, 
freedom, and growth.  The essence of technology here is not its 
labour-displacing effects but, rather, its potential as a universally 
available tool for developing new products and services and for 
redefining the way we work and live.  Globalization is not seen as a 
process benefitting capital at the expense of labour but, rather, as an 
extension of the marketplace and, with it, expanded opportunity.
<p>
	Central to the optimistic scenario is the restructuring of 
economic activity and the replacement of "job-based" production by other, 
more fluid contractual arrangements.  Bridges has coined the term 
"dejobbing" to describe this phenomenon.  The thrust of the argument is 
that we are not witnessing the "end of work" (as Rifkin's book title 
suggests) but we are beginning to see the end of jobs as the dominant way 
of organizing work.  The optimistic scenario emphasizes that "jobs" -- 
relatively permanent employment relationships with stable clusters of 
tasks -- are a social construct developed early in the industrial era to 
meet the exigencies of industrial production.  And, just as jobs did not 
really exist as an economic institution prior to industrialism, they are 
not a suitable institutional form for the postindustrial age.  Instead, 
jobs are being replaced by a web of project- or task-based contractual 
forms including self-employment, independent contractor arrangements, 
micro-enterprise employment, and other variants of nonstandard work.
<p>
	In the optimistic scenario, then, unemployment is not an issue 
because of "de-jobbing".  In theory, low incomes could be a problem for 
those who have nothing to sell in the marketplace; however, writers in 
this scenario tend to have an individualistic perspective and social and 
economic problems associated with poverty and insecurity receive 
relatively little emphasis. Considerable attention is given to 
organizational innovations that will have to emerge to accommodate the 
new forms of contracting.  Corporations are typically seen as amorphous 
if not 'virtual', shifting in shape as their activities change to exploit 
new market opportunities.
<p>
	Writers depicting an optimistic scenario do explore the 
psychological implications of de-jobbing and, true to the tradition, they 
tend to emerge with favourable interpretations. One major attribute of 
"de-jobbing", it is argued, is the personal freedom it offers.  Jobs are 
characterized as largely inflexible arrangements that create an 
artificial gap between work and the other aspects of life.  In a 
de-jobbed world, on the other hand, individuals are better able to 
integrate work with other important activities surrounding family and 
personal development.
<p>
<i>Almost Business As Usual </i>
<p>
	It is important to note that there are many observers who take a 
much less extreme view of what is going on.  For this reason, we have 
included a third scenario, "almost business as usual".  This is the 
dominant view of the future in government and within mainstream 
economics.  Perhaps the most complete articulation of this perspective in 
recent times has been the OECD's Jobs Study.  Contributions to this 
scenario tend to be more academic and quantitatively-based than is the 
case with the other two.  By using the label, "almost business as usual", 
we do not mean to suggest that proponents of this scenario are 
unconcerned about employment trends.  However, this scenario does not 
imply radically new behaviours and institutions but, rather, reforms to 
what we already have in order to meet the challenges of the changing 
environment.
<p>
	Unlike the other two, the "almost business as usual" scenario is 
an evolutionary scenario.  It recognizes that very important 
technological, social, and economic changes are taking place but it falls 
short of calling these "revolutionary".  Also different from the other 
scenarios is the almost-business-as-usual view that aggregate economic 
growth may be a problem and that governments may face significant 
constraints in terms of what they can do.
<p>
	Many of the themes emerging in this scenario can also be found in 
more extreme versions in the other two scenarios.  Unemployment and 
polarization are clearly issues of concern.   Increases in 
self-employment and nonstandard employment are also recognized although 
this development is seen in a mixed light, with some of the insecurity 
concerns of the pessimists and some of the personal flexibility 
attributes highlighted by the optimists.
<p>
	The social and psychological implications of the changing world 
of work are addressed but in a characteristically moderate fashion.  
There are concerns about what Robert Reich has called the "politics of 
secession" and the attendant threats of polarization and marginalization 
to community.  One also finds some discussion about potential health and 
social problems where persistent unemployment and underemployment exist.
<p>
<b>What Should Be Done?</b>
<p>
	Each of these scenarios has important implications for our 
institutions, policies, and behaviour.  Obviously these implications 
differ dramatically across scenarios.  In this final section, we briefly 
consider the question of what should be done, focusing on the following 
areas: job creation; education and training; providing economic and 
social security; new taxation mechanisms; and worker representation.
<p>
	Before turning to these, it is important to note that the 
responses implied by each scenario differ not only as a result of 
differences in the diagnosis of what will happen but also because of 
differences in the philosophies and values underlying each.  Those 
describing a qualified pessimistic scenario envisage bold social 
responses.  The qualified optimists, on the other hand, stress individual 
responsibility.  In the almost-business-as-usual view, there tends to be 
a mix of the two.
<p>
<i>Job Creation</i>
<p>
	In the almost business as usual scenario, the market is seen as 
the primary job creator, with governments responsible for providing a 
"fertile" environment.  In the OECD formulation, for example, this 
includes macroeconomic stability, policies that encourage innovation and 
entrepreneurship, low payroll taxes, and "flexible" labour markets.
<p>
	The qualified pessimist scenario sees the lack of jobs as a 
central -- and, in fact, intractable -- problem.  Because of 
technological progress, we only need a portion of the potential labour 
force to produce what we could possibly consume.  The solution to the 
jobs crisis, then, cannot come from the market.
<p>
	Two responses recur in the pessimistic literature.  The first is 
to more evenly share the available work.  A common theme in this scenario 
is to further reduce the work week and to introduce incentives to 
redistribute work.
<p>
	The second response is to generate paid employment in the "third 
sector" for those displaced from the labour force.  This is not only a 
(partial) solution to the shortage of jobs generated by the market but it 
would also lead to the provision of many important community and social 
services that are unlikely to be furnished by the market.  This 
employment would be funded by new taxes on the market economy -- in 
effect, by a productivity dividend.
<p>
	In the optimistic scenario, job creation is not an issue.  Trying 
to create jobs perpetuates a fantasy running directly counter to the 
emerging reality that work will no longer be bundled into jobs.  The 
appropriate economic concern for societies and their governments is 
income growth, not job growth.
<p>
<i>Education and Training</i>
<p>
	There is a consensus around the importance of education but there 
are important differences when it comes to specific priorities.  In the 
pessimistic scenario, the role of education is not primarily seen as a 
human resource development tool.  The stress is placed on education for 
community activity and overall citizenship.
<p>
	In the optimistic scenario, there is a heavy emphasis on human 
capital acquisition in order to provide individuals with the capability 
to have something to sell in the marketplace.  Basic, technical, and 
entrepreneurial skills are all accorded importance.  Education is also 
seen as the principal instrument for addressing problems of low income.  
A priority, then, is placed on ensuring that learning opportunities are 
available for those with "third world" skill levels.
<p>
	These themes are present in the almost business as usual scenario 
as well.  However, there is also an emphasis in that scenario on 
job-oriented training activities.  This, of course, is the cornerstone of 
active labour market policy.
<p>
<i>Providing Economic and Social Security</i>
<p>
	In all scenarios, the redistributive and social insurance 
approach to security that has prevailed through much of the postwar 
period in most industrialized countries is seen as either unsustainable 
or inappropriate for the future.
<p>
	In the almost business as usual scenario, fiscal pressures and 
concerns about dependency motivate the need for changes in how security 
is provided.  The major thrust of reform is from passive redistribution 
to active programs designed to support self-sufficiency through employment.
<p>
	Both the pessimistic and optimistic scenarios suggest quite a 
different approach and, in fact, these two seem to converge on some form 
of guaranteed annual income as the appropriate means of providing social 
security in the future.  In the pessimistic scenario, where jobs will be 
scarce, societies that place a value on security and support will have no 
choice but to provide everyone with a guarantee of some level of income.  
Similarly, in the optimistic scenario where incomes, not jobs, are the 
indicator of well-being, security will have to be provided through some 
form of income guarantee.  Unemployment insurance plans or any other 
program based on having a job (or losing one) would clearly be inappropriate.
<p>
<i>New Forms of Taxation</i>
<p>
	There is growing discussion of new forms of raising revenues in a 
high-technology, global economy.  This interest stems from the fact that 
the fiscal situation is very constraining for most governments, that 
traditional sources of taxation are stretched and undermined by 
globalization, and that information -- the key input in modern economic 
activity -- has largely escaped taxation.
<p>
	Accordingly, there have been some proposals for tax reform aimed 
at tapping information and thereby generating a source of revenue for 
governments to make needed human and physical capital investments and to 
have some capacity for providing economic security.  These include the 
"Tobin" tax which would be directed at international financial market 
transactions and the "bit" tax which could be applied to the flow of 
digital information over telecommunication lines.
<p>
<i>Worker Representation</i>
<p>
	Unions and collective bargaining have been the principal 
institutions for advancing the interests of labour during much of the 
industrial era.  However, the changing labour market, and particularly 
the changes in the nature of the employment contract, raise serious 
questions about the survival of these institutions, at least in their 
traditional forms.  This is true in each of the scenarios.  For example, 
the qualified pessimist scenario suggests that the challenges facing 
labour are beyond the reach of collective bargaining.  The almost 
business as usual scenario calls for more workplace partnership and a 
renewal of collective bargaining in ways that will not restrict 
enterprise or labour market flexibility.  Whether this is possible, while 
maintaining support for the membership, remains to be seen.
<p>
	It is the qualified optimist scenario, however, that poses the 
greatest challenges for unions, collective bargaining, and worker 
representation.  Existing forms of representation are predicated on an 
identifiable and stable group of employees sharing mutual interests.  
However, these conditions are clearly not present in a "de-jobbed" labour 
market.  This raises the question of how the interests of nonstandard 
employees, independent contractors, and micro-enterprise employees can be 
best represented.  It may be that the future is in "full-service" 
unionism where labour market information, assistance in matching buyers 
and sellers of skills, and the range of benefits would be provided by the 
union to an occupationally homogeneous group of workers who have an 
ongoing attachment to a set of skills and an industry but not to a 
particular employer. The union, then, would be the constant factor for an 
otherwise fluid workforce.
<p>
<b>Conclusion</b>
  <p>
	One way of looking at the future of work from a policy 
perspective is to begin with the proposition that we have not yet devised 
the institutions -- the formal and informal rules and behaviour-setting 
-- to fit with the emerging economic reality.  Just as we developed 
institutions earlier in this century to address the requirements of the 
industrial era, a new set must be invented for postindustrialism.
<p>
	Societies must decide what these institutions are and how they 
should be designed.  However, one final question concerns whether, in  a 
world of growing economic integration, there are limits to what 
individual countries alone can achieve or whether new supranational 
institutions will be necessary to ensure that the promise of technology 
and global markets will contribute to widespread well-being. 

</td>
</tr>
