<head>
<title>Introducing CPRN and the Health Network</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><h2><a name=#top_page>Introducing</a> CPRN and the Health Network</h2></center>
The mission of the CPRN is to create knowledge and lead public debate on the social dimensions of economic change. Our goal is to help strengthen the social fabric and to help make Canada a more just, prosperous and caring society.
<P>
CPRN has organized three Networks -- focused on Family, Work and Health. This Newsletter is to introduce you to the Health Network. Health is an important dimension of well-being; health services are an important part of the social fabric, and our universal access to health insurance is a source of pride for almost all Canadians.
<P>
Because health is so important to well-being, there are important linkages across the Networks. The Family Network, for example is defining the coping strategies of resilient families looking at the exchanges that take place between the individuals within families. Resiliency is clearly one of the determinants of health, and illness can often be a strain on the capacity of families to cope. The Work Network, for its part, is interested in the high performance workplace and in emerging patterns of employment and compensation in the post-industrial economy. Again, employment is linked to health, and workplace performance is affected by ill-health.
<P>
Both the Family and the Health Networks are vitally interested in the governance of the Canadian social union from two angles -- the way in which governments and citizens work out their rights and responsibilities over time; and strategies to help strengthen the social union as we adapt to more decentralized delivery of social programs.
<P>
The Networks do not function as closed boxes.  They are designed to link together the research community, centred mainly in universities, and the policy makers in federal, provincial and territorial governments. They also include social advocates and experts from the private and nonprofit sectors.
<P>
We strive to be pioneers in our research, to set high standards of research and communication through careful peer review and workshops, and to be cost-effective -- projects are ambitious in their scope, but costs and risks are spread over a number of funders.  As a nonprofit organization with charitable status, we rely on a diversity of funding. That diversity ensures that the research is independent. We also benefit immensely from the voluntary support of our Board of Directors, and members of a number of Steering and Advisory Committees.
<P>
So, welcome to the Health Network. We look forward to your feedback and your participation. Use the back page to put your name on our mailing lists or visit our homepage at <a href=../cprn2.htm>http://www.cprn.com</a>.  You can reach me directly at <a href="mailto:jmaxwell.cprn@idrc.com">jmaxwell@idrc.com</a>.
<P>
<H4>Judith Maxwell, President, CPRN </H4>
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
<P>
Health Network Newsletter <a href=newscont.htm>Table of Contents</a>
</td></tr>
