<head>
<title>Health Network Director's Report</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>Report</a> from the Director</a></H2></center>
<P>
The future of Canadas health system continues to be a topic of interest and discussion, whether it is debates over federal transfer payments for health, two-tier medicine, rising costs, waiting lists for services, or threats of a strike by unhappy doctors. The fundamental question at the core of these issues is concern about the sustainability of Canadas health system.
<P>
Here at the Health Network, we are dedicated to solid multi-disciplinary research on how Canada can keep delivering top-quality health services in times of economic restraint. We believe that the only way to arrive at solutions to complex problems is to undertake unbiased, reliable and well-designed research that fills gaps in knowledge, so that decision-making is based on accurate information.
<P>
In this, the Health Networks first newsletter, we will give you a feel for who we are and how we approach health policy issues, highlight some of our top-notch associates, and feature some of our exciting research projects. Right now we have a number of research initiatives under way, with more coming on line, as a diverse range of funding organizations recognize the Health Networks particular strengths to tackle health policy issues.
<P>
In subsequent newsletters, to be published every six months, we will discuss in more detail some of the important issues confronting current health policy and the findings of our programs.
<P>
One area in which we are now exploring research potential is that of population health. Population health seeks to explain health status and human well-being in terms of factors that encompass a persons total life experience: childhood and family, education, employment, level of wealth, coping skills, environment and such. These so-called determinants of health have been shown in recent years to have a greater impact on the health status of a population than the level of health services that are available to them. At the Health Network, we are enthusiastic about discerning the policy implications of population health through research that will complement the excellent work of others in this emerging and important field.
<P>
The design of the CPRN and its three networks reflects the understanding that health and well being are made up of different yet complementary components. Family and work are two major determinants of health that have often been ignored in the past. 
<P>
There is now an emerging understanding that the determination of a good outcome in health care needs to take a wider, holistic picture to include not only physiological results but how people interact in their environment and in the social networks that are significant to them. 
<P>
In this way, the three networks of the CPRN are consistent with this new paradigm, like three legs of a stool that unite three essential areas of well-being. For the CPRN, this interlocking arrangement is ideal to promote the development of comprehensive policies related to social well-being in Canada. 
<P>
Within the Health Network itself, this goal of seeing the big picture is made possible by embracing an interdisciplinary and interjurisdictional approach to our research, and by linking health care to the social agenda.  The Health Network team includes persons trained in medicine, nursing, epidemiology, bio-statistics, public health, economics, political science, administrative science, law, information systems, gerontology, sociology, and social policy.  Another distinctive feature of the Health Network is its emphasis on economics, systems, administration and policy.
<P>
As such, the Health Network and the CPRN are uniquely placed to undertake research in health policy that has broader implications to the lives of Canadians and social fabric of this country. <P>
<H4>Marcus Hollander, Director, Health Network</H4>
<HR width=80%>
<H3>The Networks Victoria Office</H3><P>
While our Steering Committee and Associates hail from across Canada, our administrative offices are located in Victoria in what was once a busy hospital. Now called the Fairfield Health Centre, its rich history dates back to 1876 when it opened its doors as St. Josephs Hospital.   The hospital was run by the Sisters of St. Ann, who outlined their innovative insurance program:  All persons in good health, without distinction of age, sex, creed, or colour, can become members on payment of one dollar a month.
<P>
Back then, the hospital was a two-storey building which housed 35 beds and staffed four Sisters, one doctor and a handyman.  At its peak in the 1960s, it had grown to 500 beds and a staff of more than 1,000.
<P>
In 1972, the Sisters transferred ownership to the city of Victoria and the name was changed to the Victoria General Hospital.  When a new general hospital was built on Victorias outskirts in the early 1980s, the building was turned into the Fairfield Health Centre specializing in long-term and chronic care.   In recent years most patient services have left the aging building. Yet many health agencies as well as patient groups, doctors, and specialty medical clinics continue to make their offices in the Centre.  The Health Networks offices are located on the ground floor next to a historic hospital chapel.
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
