<head>
<title>Max Bell Support for the Health Network</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>Max</a> Bell Support for the Health Network</H2></center>
<P>
In his life, Max Bell wore many hats: entrepreneur, oilman, newspaperman, sportsman and philanthropist. The Toronto-based Max Bell Foundation seeks to encourage innovative endeavours by Canadians which will lead to the development of human potential and advance our collective social, economic and academic goals.  This year, the Health Network was honoured to receive a three-year, $125,000 grant from the foundation to enable the Network to develop an enhanced capacity for health policy research.
<P>
<H3>A Program of Research in Population Health</H3>
A portion of the Max Bell grant will be used, in this fiscal year, to conduct a study to determine research priorities in the area of population health. Population health is the study of those factors such as economic status, education, family background, employment, housing and environment that play a large part in determining the health of an individual. These determinants of health generally reside outside the health system, but they have an important impact on the health status of the population. 
<P>
Health Network associate Jan Skirrow, a former deputy minister of Community and Occupational Health in Alberta, is charged with the feasibility study to  develop a program of research in population health for the Network. Skirrows training as an engineer is a good background to tackle this complex issue, since he comes from outside the health field and hence has a broader perspective of the health field that meshes well with the broad view of population health. 
Through Skirrows research, the Health Network seeks to complement the work of other health researchers in this area, such as the excellent work of the Canadian Institute for Advanced Research (CIAR) and others. The Health Networks research objective is to determine how the knowledge gained from previous work could most effectively be put into practice by decision makers.
<P>
Skirrow says there is a need to better understand the policy-making process in government in order to be effective in influencing the policy mechanisms. He also sees a need to better define the population health model.
<P>
The data in the population health model is all based on correlational data. It is at a global level. What is not known is how the determinants of health actually work. Why do they have the effect they have?
<P>
For example, notes Skirrow, the correlation between level of income and level of health has been well established. We can understand that someone in poverty would have poorer health, we would expect to see that. But why is the health of a person who is well off not as good as the person who is very well off? Why does income, even at incremental levels, have the effect it has? We need to understand this, as well as the influence of all the other determinants, much better.
<P>
Skirrow has recently completed a report on the second phase of the project, the key respondent survey.  The next process will be a workshop to bring together the breadth of expertise in the field, not only from health, but also from labor, education, employment and family to help better define the research agenda.
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
