<head>
<title>Health Network Initiatives in the Area of HIV/AIDS</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>Initiatives</a> in the Area of HIV/AIDS</H2></center><BR>
<H3>Health Network Studies Cost of HIV/AIDS</H3>
Over the last decade, the enormous toll that the human immune deficiency virus is imposing on individual Canadians and Canadian society has become increasingly apparent.  In terms of loss of life, loss of human potential, and weight of human suffering, its costs have been enormous.
<P>
But what about its economic costs? There has been a dearth of HIV/AIDS research to answer questions about the economic implications of the care, treatment and support of people with HIV and AIDS. What is the most cost-effective way to deliver HIV/AIDS care? What prevention programs are the most successful and where can the money be spent to the greatest advantage?
<P>
With health care budgets under tight restraint and the number of HIV infected individuals continuing to increase, the field of health economics has an integral part to play in the overall research effort in HIV/AIDS by providing informed and evidence-based policy information in the years ahead.
<P>
<H3>Costs of care and prevention</H3>
The Health Network has become an important player in shaping economic research in the field of HIV/AIDS. Under the Health Networks HIV/AIDS Economic Research Initiative,  there are a number of projects examining various cost-effectiveness questions.  The HIV/AIDS initiative is being directed by research coordinator Terry Albert. The research initiative is split into two general components: 1)the care, treatment and support of HIV/AIDS and 2)the prevention of HIV/AIDS. 
<HR width=80%>
<P>	
<H3>HIV/AIDS Care, Treatment, and Support</H3>
The Health Network was contracted by Health Canada to solicit, evaluate, recommend for funding, monitor and promote economic research in Canada directed at improving the quality and cost-effectiveness of HIV/AIDS care, treatment and support.
<P>
In 1995, Requests for Proposals were sent to more than 300 researchers or research groups.  The research proposals received were subjected to a formal peer review process.  The peer review results were analysed and presented to the project Advisory Committee which then conducted their own review of the proposals.  Based on these inputs, the Health Network recommended six major proposals for funding to Health Canada. The projects include studies on the economic costs and resource impact of HIV/AIDS in British Columbia; the development of an enhanced HIV/AIDS database in Ontario; the cost of community based care for persons with HIV/AIDS in Calgary; the economic evaluation of various patient management models for HIV-infected women and children in Montreal; the cost of community care programs in Edmonton and Ottawa; and cost-utility analysis of the prevention of mycobacterium avium complex infection in people living with HIV/AIDS in Toronto.  The work began early in 1996 and will be completed in March of 1998.
<P>	
<H3>Building Capacity in HIV/AIDS Care and Treatment</H3>
The Health Network has a number of other economic research projects in HIV/AIDS care and treatment which are designed to build capacity in this area by expanding the boundaries of knowledge and involving a wider range of researchers. 
<P>
A project has been launched to look at the role of informal supports in HIV/AIDS care and treatment.  Another project will be launched to assist policy makers to better estimate the incidence and prevalence of HIV/AIDS in their respective jurisdictions.
<P>
An interim report of the HIV/AIDS economic initiative will also be prepared which will provide up-to-date figures on the costs of the HIV/AIDS epidemic for Canada.
<P>	
<H3>HIV/AIDS Prevention</H3>
In the area of prevention, the Health Network has been contracted by Health CanadaÕs HIV/AIDS Prevention and Community Action Programs to undertake the initial planning for a similar national research initiative on the economic evaluation of HIV/AIDS prevention programs and strategies. This process is now underway and has already included a comprehensive literature review, the hosting of facilitated workshops, and the preparation of discussion papers.  The primary product of this project will be the development of a blue print for economic research in HIV/AIDS prevention
<HR width=80%>
<P>
<H3>Developing an Information System for HIV/AIDS Organizations</H3>
In Canada, there are more than 100 community organizations which provide education, support, and advocacy services for individuals and communities affected by HIV/AIDS. They vary greatly in size, scope, services offered and clients served. Although many of the groups collect data about their own operations, often the data cannot easily be shared between the groups because of the differences in the type of information collected, differences in the methodology of collection, and the use the data is put to. If data collection were standardized and information flow between the organizations augmented, the groups would be in a better position to develop a comprehensive community-based response to AIDS in Canada. The Health Network and the Canadian AIDS Society are collaborating on a project to develop a pilot survey instrument to provide information on such matters.  Funded by Health Canada, the project will help develop a standardized method to collect, analyze and store data that can be used by community-based AIDS organizations.  The project, which is expected to be completed by fall 1997, will build on information already in use at AIDS service organizations and draw on community knowledge and experience.
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
