<head>
<title>Puzzling Issues Initiative of the Health Network</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>Puzzling</a> Issues Initiative of the Health Network</h2></center><BR>
<H3>Health Care Puzzles</H3>
Like Canada, most developed countries are struggling to keep health care costs under control while still delivering quality care, yet comparing international data and experience is problematic. Six technical papers, which were commissioned by the National Health Forum, compared Canadas health care system to other OECD countries using several dimensions. These papers revealed five puzzling questions concerning Canada within an international perspective. These questions include: Why does Canada have one of the worlds top expenditures on health when we do not have significantly more physicians or hospital beds than other industrialized nations? Why do the same health services have such different prices in different countries? Why do some countries, with more elderly populations than Canada, spend the same or less on health care as Canada? Would a more even distribution of funding across the service continuum (hospitals, physicians, drugs, community based care etc.) improve cost control without compromising access? Since health expenditures are not correlated with a countrys health status, what does this tell us about the proper allocation of public spending and social/fiscal policies to achieve better health outcomes? 
<P>
The National Health forum commissioned the Health Network to prepare papers and fact sheets on these five puzzling issues. Those papers have recently been completed and the Forums final report is expected to be published early in 1997. 
<P>
