<head>
<title>Health Network Initiative in Employment and Health</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center>
<a name=#top_page><H2>Health</a> Network Initiative in Employment and Health</h2></center><BR>
<H3>Employment and Health</H3> 
Last March the Health Network, in partnership with the Institute for Work and Health in Toronto, conducted a Health Canada-sponsored Workshop on Employment and Health. More than 20 participants gathered to explore, discuss and gain consensus on the various linkages between work, employment, and health, and to identify future directions and priorities for policy research.  A number of background papers were reviewed by Workshop participants and presentations were made on:  the conceptual overview of work and health; a research framework for work and health; the implications of changes in working time; the role of the state; and the possibility of bringing about changes to policies related to work.
<P>
The day-long workshop was excellent at canvassing the broad spectrum of issues surrounding this very complex topic and generating a wealth of detail about the relationships between work and health, comments Lucinda Montizambert, of the Division of Program and Policy Analysis of Health Canada, for whom the workshop was held. According to Montizambert, so many issues arose that we hadnt anticipated --overwork, underwork, unpaid work, child welfare issues, the whole complexity of this broad social and global issue -- we realized we needed to attempt to map the relationships, to get a handle on all the pieces and how they fit together.  That project of mapping the relationships has recently been completed in a Health Canada report, building on the foundation set by the workshop and will help focus subsequent policy research efforts. The workshop and its report were very important to get the ball rolling, said Montizambert. 
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
<P>
