<html>
<head>
<title>Decision Support Tools - Initiative</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>Decision</a> Support Tools: Promises and Pitfalls</H2></center>
One of the most important philosophies in modern health care is to avoid unnecessary medical intervention and expense, while giving the patient the most appropriate care to produce the best outcome.  But arriving at decisions to support that philosophy isnt always easy.
<P>
Consider the following dilemma: a general practitioner in a remote area of Canada isnt sure whether to order an air ambulance to transport a patient to a tertiary hospital.  Most doctors in this situation err on the side of caution and order the flight, yet studies show a significant number of evacuations are not necessary and can put a strain on both the patient and resources. That scenario, says Dr. Paul Fisher, Director of the School of Health Information Science at the University of Victoria, and an associate of the Health Network, is a good example of where a Decision Support Tool (DST) might help.
<P>
<H3>Computers as conduits</H3>
DSTs are a new innovation in health informatics which use computers as a conduit for a step-by-step process of decision-making. Relying on a data bank of knowledge and information that has been gleaned from experts and structured into a computer interface, DSTs aim to help the non-expert reach a quality decision. In the above scenario, for example, the lone doctor would enter into the computer all the available parameters on the patients condition and, in turn, would receive an assessment of the relative risk of keeping the patient put, or undertaking the evacuation. Not only that, but the doctor can then enter the results of the eventual decision into the data bank, enabling the computer to learn from past experience.
<P>
While there is a great deal of enthusiasm about DSTs, their efficacy has not yet been empirically demonstrated, nor are they yet in wide use. That was part of the conclusions of a study of DSTs conducted by the Health Network for the National Health Forum this last year. Fisher was principal investigator of the study, which analyzed 86 DSTs in the literature; co-investigators were Dr. Tom MacKenzie of Queens University, Marcus Hollander of the Health Network, and Dr. Peter Kleinstiver of Katalyst Professional Services.
<P>
<H3>Few in Use</H3>
The study found that most DSTs were developed for clinical applications, but even then only 24 per cent were in actual use. An even smaller amount had been subjected to independent external evaluations. Most DSTs were still in development. 
<P>
The study found that DSTs show promise, particularly in the area of clinical care, where there are few conflicts of interests and a high degree of agreement about the need, efficacy and appropriateness of the scientific approach. Yet where there are conflicting ideas or beliefs, or differing value systems - such as is often found in strategic planning or administration - the use of DSTs may be far more problematic.
<P>
One of the most important contributions of the study was its formulation of 12 key steps for the planning of a successful DST development, including clearly identifying the problem the DST will address, ensuring there is support within the organization to use the tool, and conducting systematic evaluations of the outcomes.
<P>
Dr. Fisher and others will be using these 12 key steps as they develop DSTs in the future. Dr. Fisher is working on international collaborative projects to develop health-related DSTs in such places as Brazil and Argentina. As well, here in Canada, Dr. Fisher and Dr. MacKenzie are developing a DST to be used in Northern Saskatchewan by doctors, hospitals and clinics to aid in the diagnosis and treatment of asthma and the collection of data about its incidence.
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
<P>
Health Network Newsletter <a href=newscont.htm>Table of Contents</a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=../cprn2.htm>
<img src=../pics/home.gif alt=[Home]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
</td></tr>
