</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Study of Services for Children with Special Needs</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>Study </a>of Services for Children with Special Needs</h2></center>
<P>
When a child has special needs, the childs family or health care providers can be at a loss to know what services are available in the region to help the child and family or how to maximize their use.
<P>
Services are often split between government jurisdictions, with educational needs being looked after by one ministry, health care by another, and social and community needs by a third.
<P>
To make matters more difficult, various provinces have different programs and approaches so that services will vary widely between rural and urban settings and from province to province. Putting  together an integrated picture of what is best for the child with disabilities has been hard for families, institutions and governments alike.
<P>
With funding from Health Canada and the Canadian Association for Community Care (CACC), the Health Network has embarked on a study to examine the current state of services for children with special needs across Canada. The first component of the study was a survey of the literature to compile descriptions of all possible services available to children with special needs. The second component consists of an overview of the service delivery systems for children with special needs in each province and territory, with comparative descriptions of what services are available in each jurisdiction and how they are organized.  The third component is a literature review of the cost effectiveness of various services for children with special needs. 
<P>
The principal researcher for the study is Health Network associate Dr. Virginia Hayes, an assistant professor in the School of Nursing at the University of British Columbia. Dr. Hayes has been interested in the care of children and their families for 30 years, particularly the impact of chronic conditions within families. Co-investigators on the project are Eden Cloutier, Marcus Hollander and Elsie Tan.
<P>
The report of the Services for Children With Special Needs, scheduled for release in early 1997, will include suggestions for a best practices model of service delivery.
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
<P>
