</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Health Goals - John Millar</title>
<body  background=../pics/back4.gif text=#661621>
<P>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=left valign=top>
<a href=../about/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/about.gif  alt=[About] vspace=5 hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../family/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/family2.gif alt=[Family]  hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../health/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/health2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../work/index.htm>
<img src=../pics/work2.gif alt=[Health]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0></a><br>
<a href=../mailcprn.htm>
<img src=../pics/feedbac2.gif alt=[Feedback]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>
<!--a href=../search.htm-->
<!--img src=../pics/search2.gif alt=[Search]   hspace=20 width=70 border=0 ></a><br>-->
</td>
<td>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>
<td align=top>
<center><a name=#top_page><H2>B.C. Forges</a> Path with Health Goals</h2></center>
In each newsletter, we will focus on an innovative area of health research that is being conducted in Canada by members of the Health Network family.  Though separate from the Health Network, these are projects that may influence the path of health policy in the future. In this issue, we examine the work being done on Health Goals by B.C. Provincial Health Officer Dr. John Millar and his team, which includes Jan Skirrow and Michael Hayes, associates of the Health Network. Dr. Millar is a member of the Health Network Steering Committee.  
<P>
During the last decade, studies on the determinants of health have shown that spending more money for hospitals, equipment or high-tech health services wont necessarily improve the health of the population. It has become increasingly clear that to improve the quality and the duration of peoples lives, more attention must be paid to areas outside the health care field. Employment, education, income disparity, housing, healthy environments, and other factors outside the traditional health care system have all been found to have a tremendous impact on whether a person enjoys good health or not.
<P>
But how do governments go about translating those research findings into concrete policies with measurable indicators that actually make a difference to the health status of the population?  
<P>
<H3>Royal Commission leads</H3>
In 1991, in British Columbia, the Royal Commission On Health Care and Costs recommended that the province establish health goals -- identifiable targets for the improvement of the health status of the population that are stated in measurable terms and incorporated into a time-scale for achievement.
<P>
At the same time, the commission also recommended the creation of a health watch dog for the province who would report annually about the health of British Columbians as measured against the population health goals. The Office of the Provincial Health Officer, under Dr. John Millar, was chosen as the logical body to become both the health watchdog and the group responsible for coordinating the development of the health goals.
<P>
The process began in November 1994 with a meeting of about 50 British Columbians from all sectors of society, including representatives of health care, industry, social services, education, housing, early childhood development, justice, aboriginal people, women, low income groups, and the environment. A set of draft health goals was established which then became the basis of a more in depth consultation process with officials of all government ministries, stakeholders and the public.
<P>
<H3>Tied to targets and indicators</H3>
Notes Millar, virtually every province in recent years has been developing health goals, but these largely have been broad statements of intent. Where B.C. has tried to be innovative is in closely tying targets, indicators, and benchmarks to measure the provinces progress. For example, under the health goals, one target could be to reduce the rate of teen pregnancy, the indicator would be B.C. teen pregnancy rate, which currently stands at 50 per 1000. The benchmark would be the best rate known, such as the Netherlands 12 per 1,000. In each of the goals established, a detailed list of targets, indicators and benchmarks is being identified. The indicators go far beyond the standard infant mortality rates, life expectancy and other health status indicators used to gauge population health and include, among a large list, gross domestic product, vehicle emission standards, waiting lists for subsidized housing and literacy rates.
<P>
The B.C. process of having targets, indicators and benchmarks, we hope, takes it to a much different level than other provinces, says Millar, who is optimistic that successful implementation of the goals will lead to the next great leap in public health.  The most interesting process for Millar himself has been establishing outcome indicators for use in hospitals and by health care professionals. Traditionally the health care system has not been expected to be accountable for its outcome, he says.
<P>
The health goals project is in its final stages and is now before the B.C. Cabinet for approval. 
<P>
To return to the top of this section, <a href=#top_page>click here</a>.
<P>
