<td align=top>

<center><h3>Shepherds of Good Hope<br>
      The Social Transformation of the 90s: Jobs? or Pieces of Work?</br>
                     Speaking Notes for Judith Maxwell<br>
                            September 28, 1995</h3></center>

I am honoured to have this opportunity to pay tribute to the work of the Shepherds of Good Hope.  They care for a large number of people in this community who need a helping hand.  And, tonight, I will be linking some of my research at CPRN to some of the experiences we can see in the streets of Ottawa.
<p>
The mission of the CPRN is to do excellent research and to lead public debate on the social dimensions of economic change.  Our aim is to help make Canada a more just, prosperous, and caring society. <p>
My text is taken from a prayer we said at St. Matthew's Church in the Glebe last Sunday:  
<p><ul>
   <i>"Let not the needy, O Lord, be forgotten; <br>
     Nor the hope of the poor be taken away."</i>
</ul><dl>
<dt>I'd like to begin with three anecdotes:
<p>
<dd>     When I was buying my groceries one day in April, I overheard one of the cashiers explaining to an old friend:  "Well, I graduated from Carleton a year ago, and ....." the rest got lost in the noise.  <p>
    <dd> A young economist, just laid off by the federal government, came to see me for advice.  " I think I am beginning to understand it," he said, 
"I'm not looking for a job, I'm looking for pieces of work." <p>
   <dd>  The coordinator of volunteers at a major social service agency in 
Ottawa.  "I have never seen anything like it.  In the past year, over 
100 young people with university degrees have volunteered here because 
they can't find jobs that use their training." </dl>
There you have it.  The youth of Canada -- unemployed, underemployed, 
educated, and eager. <p>
Now, I would like to give you some data on the experience of the 3,100 
federal public servants in the National Capital Region who left 
full-time, indeterminate jobs in the downsizing of 1991 and 1992.  The 
figures are based on a Statistics Canada Tracking Study done in July, 1994.
<p>
One third of these people decided to retire.  Of those who did look for 
work, 17 percent never found jobs, 29 percent opted for self-employment, 
and 54 percent found paid employment.  At the time of the survey, 21 
percent of those who wanted to work were unemployed.
<p>
Of those who found a paid job, 31 percent work part-time and 45 percent 
are in term jobs.  This tracking study is a story of greater economic 
insecurity.  We can only assume that the situation will be even more 
precarious for the 15,000 who will lose their jobs in the coming year.
<p>
My own grapevine from Economic Council of Canada employees who lost 
their jobs in 1992 indicates that the professionals have done pretty 
well.  The people who are unemployed or most insecure are from the 
administrative and clerical groups who have lower skills and less education.
<p>
These young people and these public servants are all living examples of 
the extraordinary social transformation of the 20th century.  It is not 
unique to Canada  -- for the most part, it is driven by technology,  and 
by world competition.   In Canada, we have the complication of excessive 
public debt and the need to restructure governments. <p>

What I would like to do this evening is map out some of the 
repercussions of this social transformation, and then speculate about 
what you and I and others in this community can do to counter this insecurity.  
<p>
<b>The Shamrock Economy</b>
<p>
Here in Canada, employers are reorganizing work into three categories, 
which Charles Handy has called The Shamrock Economy.  The first leaf of 
the Shamrock includes the old-fashioned full-time, full-year secure jobs 
that remain. Most of these jobs are knowledge work -- in managerial, 
professional, technical, and administrative positions.  Many of these 
people are teachers and nurses, for example, protected by strong 
collective agreements. <p>
The second leaf of the Shamrock involves contractual work.  Many 
formerly core jobs have been contracted out to professionals and 
technicians who now work "by the piece" for a number of different 
clients.  Most of what they do is knowledge work.  Still, contractual 
work is piece work.  <p>
The remaining leaf involves non-standard jobs.  This leaf included about 
30 percent of all jobs in Canada in 1993.  The jobs are part-time or 
short-term with limited or no benefits and usually low wages.  These 
workers are often referred to as the contingent work force.  They too 
have pieces of work. <p>
Many of the people in these jobs are poorly educated, others are educated but overqualified for the work they do -- like the grocery clerk I mentioned earlier.  <p>
<b>Social dimensions of knowledge work</b>
<p>
Why should we worry about all this?  Well, the economic polarization can 
eventually lead to class conflict.  It polarizes society into those who 
are educated and\or trained, and those who are not, into insiders and 
outsiders.  <p>
Until this year, it was tempting to assume the outsiders were taken care 
of by a reasonably comprehensive social safety net.  It is true that the 
soaring cost of transfer payments has offset the polarization of 
earnings from work.  Consequently, there is not yet much evidence of 
rising inequality in incomes after taxes and transfers are included.  <p>
I would be prepared to argue that this view of the social safety net has 
been an illusion for some time.  Our safety net has been based, to a 
considerable extent, on the needs of the old industrial economy.  <p>
It has offered what I call palliative care.  We send people cheques 
while they wait for a job.  Such a policy has no hope of bridging the 
yawning gaps between haves and have nots being created by the 
marketplace of today.  Social programs definitely need to be reformed.
<p>
But this year, even the illusion of security has been torn away.  
Welfare benefits for many Ontarians will be cut by 21 percent as of next 
Sunday.  Further cuts to unemployment insurance are planned, and many 
related social services are likely to be curtailed.
<p>
The growing prevalence of pieces of work means that families with paid 
work (sometimes two paid workers) may still be poor.  Real income per 
family has fallen, on average, over the past 15 years, and the real 
incomes of young families have fallen precipitously.  <p>

Even the families that have adequate income, however, find they are 
stretched.  If it takes the combined incomes of both parents to keep the 
family whole, some at least are struggling with another kind of deficit 
--  the lack of family time for nurturing, sharing and care giving, and 
the lack of community supports to help cope with unexpected crises. <p>
This isolation develops because families are breaking up into smaller 
units.  But it is aggravated by two other facts of modern life:  In 
urban settings, there is often little or no communication with 
neighbours down the hall or across the street.  And people in 
non-standard work are more isolated because they can no longer count on 
the friendships made at work.  <p>
This combination of problems -- economic insecurity, pieces of work, too 
little family time and too few community supports -- adds up to what I 
have come to call the social deficit. <p>
We do not have measures of the social deficit, but we know that the 
needy people experiencing the social deficit are poor, and that many 
others are not.  There are lots of anecdotes.  Teachers see it every day 
in the classroom as kids arrive unfocused, unready to learn.  You hear 
about drug and alcohol dependency among 12 and 13 year olds, or see the 
rising number of panhandles on Bank Street, or read about lawless 
activity in the streets of Ottawa.  Believe me, not all of these kids 
come from poor homes.<p>

One measure of the social deficit, albeit a crude one comes from the 
Ekos study called Rethinking Government which is based on survey data.  
Ekos divided the population into clusters according to their 
socio-economic status.  Fully 41 percent of the population fell into two 
groups which are living at the margins of Canadian society. <p><ul>
       <li>   19 percent were "Outsiders", people who no longer have ties or 
commitments to the system.  There are many young people in this group.  
They are highly concentrated in Ontario, Quebec, and Atlantic Canada.
<li>          Another 22 percent were " Disengaged Dependents,"  living on 
government programs with no sense of an alternative.  This included a 
lot of minority groups, women and Atlantic Canadians. </ul>
What an incredible waste!  41 percent of the population no longer feel 
connected to mainstream society.  As one of my Board members said last 
week,  the society we built in the post-war period is falling down 
around our ears. <p>
What is falling down around our ears, in effect, is the natural 
stabilisers: 1) The welfare state is being curtailed by fiscal pressures; 
2) the commitment of employers to stable jobs with a good wage has been 
reduced by the pressures of technology and global competition; and 3) 
families are smaller and less stable than they used to be. <p>
To be honest with you, I do not see any self-correcting mechanism that 
will reverse this stress on our society.  A period of strong economic 
growth could prevent it from getting worse, but you know as well as I do 
that some of the dividends from economic growth in the next decade will 
be used to pay down the public debt. <p>

The risk is that we are now moving from economic polarization to social 
polarization -- the class conflict I referred to earlier. Insiders, with 
nice homes and stable communities, will start to build walls around 
themselves to keep out the outsiders.  They will complain about unsafe 
streets, and worry themselves sick about the safety of their children. <p>
Well, after this scenario of unmitigated gloom, you must be wondering 
why you came here this evening.  I am not trying to depress you.  In the 
tradition of the Shepherds, I want to offer you some hope.  To be frank, 
I want to shock you into action, so that we can create new kinds of 
stabilizers.  We can begin to take personal and collective 
responsibility for the trends in our own communities.  <p>

<b>An agenda for action</b>
<p>
What sort of action?  Well, there is no lack of understanding about the services and supports the outsiders need. Here are some of the ideas which are known to work.  They provide the beginnings of an agenda for action.
 <p>
To put it simply, people need jobs.  They need help in finding jobs. They also need support systems that help them cope with the lack of family time and the lack of emotional and community supports.  Some of this stuff is pretty low-tech, but it works.
<p>
Most of the ideas are centred around education and support systems that help people take charge of their own lives.  They are basically community investments that create opportunities to learn.  They create hope.  They give outsiders a second chance.
<p>
The first three depend entirely on the willingness of employers (big and small) to create opportunities for young people:
<p>
<ol>
<li>Cooperative education, where students are offered work terms while they 
are in high school or in post-secondary education.  Here employers have to offer placements with meaningful work experience.
<p>
<li>Internships which offer a six to twelve month opportunity for a new 
graduate to learn under the guidance of an experienced worker.  This gives the employer a chance to test someone out before making a formal offer.  Even if no job is forthcoming, the
 intern has had a productive work experience, which will help him or her to land the next job.
<p>
<li>Adopt a school in the neighbourhood.  This means that designated classes 
would have a chance to visit the workplace and see the world of work as it really is.  
<p>
The next five ideas require collective action by community organizations, volunteers, schools, and employers:
<p>

<li>After-school programs for adolescents can fill the gap between the end 
of the school day and the time that the parent gets home from work.  <p>
<li>Homework clubs can help kids who are struggling in school to gain skills 
that are missing, keep up with the class, and build self-esteem. <p>
<li>Day care cooperatives for sole-support parents with young children, 
create opportunities to take a training course or get a part-time job. <p>
<li>Elder care services which help the elderly to remain independent, and 
give respite to the adults responsible for ongoing care.  These 
services involve help with shopping, transportation, household 
maintenance and so on. <p>
<li>Mentoring programs for people who are unemployed.  Mentors can help with 
the job search, help to identify training opportunities etc.  <p>
<li>Freenet support groups for isolated groups in the community, such as 
caregivers for Alzheimer patients or sole support mothers. 
</ol><p>
Clearly, as you can see from this list, there is work to be done.  And 
the list is not all inclusive.  Each neighbourhood will have its own 
needs.  It is up to the people in that neighbourhood to identify the 
needs, and then begin to identify the people who can help meet those 
needs.  Then, they can begin to look for help. <p>
What is needed, in most cases, is some equipment, some meeting rooms, 
large amounts of organizing skills, willing men and women who care 
enough to help, and some modest amounts of money.
 <p>
What resources do we have available in the community to organize and 
operate these kinds of programs? <p>
Well we have large numbers of employers who have a clear interest in a 
safe, healthy community which produces workers with good habits of 
working and learning, workers who have enough supports around them to be 
able to concentrate while they are on the job.  If employers offer 
pieces of work, then they have a clear responsibility to make community 
investments.
We also have union leaders who have been left in disarray by the 
breakdown of collective bargaining in the public service.  They have 
organizing skills which would be invaluable.  They also need a new 
mission in life. <p>
We have large numbers of retirees aged 55 or so, who still have good 
health, energy, and a considerable experience with organizing and 
operating public services.  Another 3-4,000 public servants will be 
taking voluntary departure this year or next.  Could they not give some of
their spare time to the community? <p>
We have rising numbers of unemployed people, who will become 
increasingly desperate for work and a sense of value in the community. 
There is no lack of useful work to be done. Can we not offer them a 
modest wage?  Or can we not offer them work to earn their social assistance benefits so they can begin to feel that they are earning their way in society?
<p>
We have teachers and principals in the schools across the region who are 
desperately worried about their capacity to minister to the social needs 
of their students as well as teach them the basic curriculum.  They have 
to begin to share this burden with people out in the community who care 
enough to take on at least part of the responsibility. <p>
We have unemployed nurses who cannot find work at the same time that our home care and other community-based health services are crying out for more coherence and more resources.  
<p>
We have employers, especially the federal government, which probably have large numbers of obsolete desktop computers which could be used by community groups to connect with the local Freenet.
<p>
We have more than a dozen municipal governments with big budgets, governments which compete with each other, when they could be partnering.
<p>
And, finally, we have dozens of community institutions like the Shepherds of Good Hope.  They are struggling with their big hearts and their limited resources to respond to needs that are growing relentlessly.  
<p>
As fundraising becomes more difficult, some of these agencies will have to look for ways to collaborate with others.
<p>
<b>Concluding Thoughts</b>
<p>
In conclusion, then, the social transformation of the 1990s is leaving many people in this region with pieces of work.  We know there are not enough of the old jobs to go around.  But we should not punish the victims and leave them to flounder.  
<p>
Nor can we expect big government to handle the problem.  There is much that governments must do to mitigate these stresses, and I spend most of my waking hours trying to generate research to help them make informed choices.  But governments have their limits.  They do not function well 
at the grassroots. <p>
Nor can we eliminate the pieces of work problem.  We cannot ask employers to ignore the pressures of competition.
<p>
Nor can we solve the problem by building walls to keep the outsiders from intruding into our comfortable middle class lives.
<p>
The hope for the future of this community and for countless others across the country will lie in our ability to look after each other.
<p>
As society transforms, so must our social institutions.  We are proud that Canada is a caring nation, a nation that shares.  For decades, though,  we have done much of our caring indirectly, through paying taxes and making contributions to the United Way.
  <p>
For the 21st century, however, we have to find new ways to take personal 
and collective responsibility for the health of our community.  We must 
invest in community bridges which bring the outsiders back into the 
mainstream, even if they have to survive on pieces of work.
<p>
In short, let not their hope, our hope, be taken away.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;
<P>
To return to the top of this document, <a href="#top_page">click here</a>.
</td>
