"../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD></TR><TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP"><TD><A HREF="../../audio_clips/audio-clips.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/audio.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Audio Clips" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.capaccess.org/cgi-bin/ldonline/netforum/ldf/a/1"><IMG SRC="../../images/bulletin.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Bulletin Board" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../ld_store/LD-Store.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/store.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="LD Store" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.weta.capaccess.org/ldonline/ld_survey.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/talk.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Talk Back" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../kidzone/kidzone.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/kid.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Kid Zone"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE><BR><!-MENU Bar Ends Here> <BR><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="540" HEIGHT="3" VSPACE="0"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Technology Assistance for<BR>Learning and Behavior</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Maggie Kyger<BR>Technology Specialist<BR><FONT COLOR="#000000">James Madison University <BR>December 1996</FONT></B></P><P ALIGN=CENTER>&nbsp;</P><P><FONT COLOR="#000000">Computers and other multi-media technology offermotivating, individual, and most importantly, low-risk learning opportunitiesfor students with learning and behavior disorders. Computers are non-judgmental,easily facilitate error correction, and can provide immediate, specificfeedback. One of the main goals of special education is to prepare studentswith disabilities for daily life in the &quot;outside&quot; world. It isoften very difficult to provide the realistic contexts needed to teach manyof these skills, and to create motivating, individualized learning opportunitiesfor students with a variety of unique needs. Multimedia technology is avaluable tool for special educators to utilize when teaching functionalskills or providing remedial or compensatory instruction. </FONT></P><P><FONT COLOR="#000000">Students with disabilities often have difficultieswith motivation and are frequently described as passive, dependent learners.Many computer programs allow a student to determine the pace, sequence andcontent of instruction. Providing students with this control as well asongoing, visual representations of their progress can enhance their motivationand assist in teaching them independence.</FONT></P><P><FONT COLOR="#000000">Interactive technology gives students hands-onexperience. Because information is delivered in an exciting context, retentionof information is enhanced. There are many interactive software programsavailable for all grade levels and topics. Programs range from math tutorialssuch as Math Rabbit (the Learning Company) to books such as Mercer Mayer'sJust Grandma and Me (Broderbund, Living Books), and Edmark's ImaginationExpress Series Destination: Time Trip USA or Destination: Neighborhood.Programs such as Thinkin' Things (Edmark) provide students with opportunitiesto enhance memory and listening skills and develop problem solving skillswhile students with written language deficits improve their skills whenusing authoring programs such as The Amazing Writing Machine (Broderbund).<BR><BR>Multimedia technology also allows students to work together cooperativelyand interact across age levels. Access to the Internet opens even more doorsto learning. Students can develop &quot;keypals&quot;- an electronic versionof penpals that provides opportunities for practice in writing in real contextswhile learning about other communities and countries. KIDLINK at http://www.kidlink.orgis a global keypal network for students aged 10-15. Gathering informationfrom the Internet or from other multi-media sources such as CD-rom encyclopediasor video disks provides students with alternatives to standard curriculumsources. Using a digital camera or importing video footage into a computerprogram can provide students with realistic visual inputs for writing tasksas well as functional contexts to practice needed skills. Using a videocamera and a program such as C U See Me, students can observe and interactwith other people on-line. These and other projects allow students realisticcommunity access within a school setting.<BR><BR>There is an abundance of information and resources available for teacherson the Internet. The CEC home page is a good starting point for specialeducation information (http://www.cec.sped.org/home.htm). For general curriculuminformation , the education sub-directory of Yahoo (http://www.yahoo.com/Education)is a good place to start searching as are Web Sites and Resources for Teachers(http://www.csun.edu/~vceed009/index.html) or Ask ERIC (http://ericir.syr.edu/).</FONT></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><TT><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR></FONT></TT><B><FONT COLOR="#000000">LD OnLine</FONT></B><FONT COLOR="#000000">thanks <B>Maggie Kyger</B> for contributing this article.</FONT><BR><HR SIZE="3" NOSHADE></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=-2>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT></BODY></HTML>
