A>,  NICHCY Briefing Paper, National Information Center for Children and Youth  with Disabilities, 1995</B> - This paper includes a look at learning disabilities  in children and youth, suggestions for parents on how to help their school-age  children learn, and considerations for adults with reading and learning  problems, including a description of the diagnostic process for adults.  Contributing authors include Dr. Larry Silver and Sally Smith.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="gen-4.html">Disabilities which Qualify Children and Youth for  Education Services under the Individuals with Disabilities Act (IDEA)</A>,</B>  <B>National Information Center for Children and Youth with Disabilities,  1995 - </B>This article gives a general breakdown of the disabilities that  qualify for IDEA as well as information for parents of infants, toddlers,  and preschoolers who have similar disabilities.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="gen-nimh-booklet.html">Learning Disabilities, Decade of the  Brain</A>, Information Booklet, National Institutes of Mental Health, National  Institutes of Health, September 1993 -</B> This booklet gives parents and  teachers alike general information about learning disabilities. The entire  booklet is online and is prefaced by an outline of booklet information.  <BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="eric_ldgen.html">Learning Disabilities</A>, ERIC Digest #E516  -</B> This digest provides an overview of the federal definition of learning  disabilities, viewpoints on identifying learning disabilities, and various  ways of serving individuals with learning disabilities. <BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="future_children.html">Learning Disabilities</A>, G. Reid Lyon,  Ph.D., The Future of Children, Special Education for Students with Disabilities,  Vol. 6, No. 1, Spring 1996 </B>- This article offers a review of the development  of the field of learning disabilities, research discoveries at the NIH  LD Research Centers, and offers recommendations for the future.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="gen-1.html">Learning Disorders and the Flow of Expectations</A>,  Dr. Melvin D. Levine, F.A.A.P., Their World Magazine, 1990, National Center  for Learning Disabilities - </B>This article details the developmental  expectations of children as they grow and how those expectations are hard  on children with learning disabilities. It discusses language, memory,  attention, fine motor skills, and thinking skills development in children  with learning disabilities.</MENU><H3>Early Warning Signs:</H3><MENU>  <P><A HREF="lavoie_early.html"><B>What Are the &quot;Early Warning Signs&quot;  of Learning Disabilities?</B></A><B>, Richard Lavoie, Teacher's Guide to  Last One Picked ... First One Picked On, 1994 - </B>Richard Lavoie reviews  the wide range of symptoms exhibited by children with learning disabilities.  <P><A HREF="early_childhood_inter.html"><B>Early Childhood Intervention</B></A><B>,  Learning Disabilities Assoc. of America</B> - This pamphlet offers helpful  information about the common characteristics of preschoolers who might  be at risk for being identified as having a learning disability.</MENU><H3>Learn more about it:</H3><MENU>  <P><A HREF="../../finding_help/publications_help/pubs_index_help.html"><B>Our  selected publications</B></A> offer an array of sources to learn more.</MENU><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT SIZE="3" WIDTH="540%" NOSHADE></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=-2>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT></BODY></HTML>
