VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"><P>
<H2><CENTER>Assessment</CENTER>
</H2>
Assessing children for the presence of a learning disability is explored
in-depth here, including the school and parent roles, terminology, and the
requirements of federal law. An understanding of this process if essential
for both parents and educators. 
<H3>For Starters:</H3>
<MENU><A HREF="assess-nichcy.html"><B>Assessing Children for the Presence
of a Disability</B></A><B>, NICHCY News Digest Volume 4, Number 1, 1994
- </B>This News Digest looks at the ways and primary skill areas in which
school systems assess children for the presence of a disability. The parents'
role in the assessment process is also discussed, as are concerns associated
with assessing children who are culturally and linguistically diverse. The
issue concludes with an extensive reference list and a brief list of organizations
that may be able to provide information on the assessment of specific disabilities.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="assessproc-ncld.html">The Assessment Process</A>, We Can Learn,
Part 3 (1991), National Center for Learning Disabilities - </B>This article
is the third in a series of five that NCLD has included with their video
collection, We Can Learn. It details the most frequently asked questions
about diagnosis and assessment of students with learning disabilities, including
the specific tests that students may take for placement purposes. 
</MENU>
<H3>For Parents:</H3>
<MENU><A HREF="assessment%20Q%27s.html"><B>Questions To Ask When Having
Your Child Assessed</B></A><B>, Parents' Educational Resource Center (PERC)
</B>- Useful list of questions to ask when having your child assessed for
the presence of learning disabilities. <BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="adhd_assessment.html">Questions to Ask When Selecting A Professional
To Assess Or Treat ADHD</A>, Parents' Education Resource Center (PERC) -</B>
Useful list of questions to ask when having your child assessed for the
presence of Attention Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD). 
</MENU>
<P>
