<IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="540" HEIGHT="3"
VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"><P>
<H2><CENTER><BR>
Family Relationships</CENTER>
</H2>
Here we explore the many facets of family life; the impact of a child with
learning disabilities on the family and the importance of familial support
and understanding in the development of a child with special needs.  Sibling
relationships are also investigated.
<H3>For Starters:</H3>
<MENU><A HREF="family-1.html"><B>The Learning Disabled Child and the Home</B></A><B>,
Cheryl G. Tuttle and Penny Paquette, Their World1994,<I> </I>National Center
for Learning Disabilities, 1994 - </B>This article focuses on the role the
family plays in a learning disabled child's daily life. It suggests that
fathers be active in helping the child. Included are other suggestions for
parents. The language is easy to read and understand. 
</MENU>
<H3>Sibling Relationships:</H3>
<MENU><A HREF="family-sib1.html"><B>Children with Disabilities: Understanding
Sibling Issues</B></A><B>, NICHCY News Digest, National Information Center
for Children and Youth with Disabilities, 1994 - </B>Many factors which
affect sibling relationships are described. Guidelines and suggestions for
parents and siblings, and siblings' suggestions for parents are discussed.
<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="mybrother.html">My Brother Is Different</A>, Betty B. Osman,
Ph.D., Their World 1988, National Center for Learning Disabilities - </B>This
article discusses the impact of familial atmosphere and the prevailing attitudes
associated with sibling relationships. Betty B. Osman is also the author
of &quot;Learning Disabilities: A Family Affair&quot; and &quot;No One to
Play With - The Social Side of Learning Disabilities.&quot; 
</MENU>
<BR>

<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="540" ALIGN=LEFT NOSHADE>
