="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD></TR><TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP"><TD><A HREF="../../audio_clips/audio-clips.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/audio.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Audio Clips" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.capaccess.org/cgi-bin/ldonline/netforum/ldf/a/1"><IMG SRC="../../images/bulletin.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Bulletin Board" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../ld_store/LD-Store.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/store.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="LD Store" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.weta.capaccess.org/ldonline/ld_survey.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/talk.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Talk Back" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../kidzone/kidzone.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/kid.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Kid Zone"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE><BR><!-MENU Bar Ends Here> <BR><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="540" HEIGHT="3" VSPACE="0"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"><BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><BR>Teaching Techniques</H2><P>There's no shortage of information on teaching techniques for studentswith learning disabilities. Here we've assembled some basics - &quot;forstarters&quot; - and provided direction to an array of teaching resourcesonline. This section will also serve to highlight newly published worksfrom leading researchers in the field.</P><H3><BR>For Starters:</H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><A HREF="helping_parents.html"><B>Helping Parents Deal with the Fact  That Their Child Has a Disability</B></A>,<B> Bill Healey, CEC Today, Vol.  3 No. 5, November 1996</B> - Tips for teachers and other professionals  on helping parents accept their child's disability. </P>  <P><A HREF="teaching-1.html"><B>What Teachers Can Do About Learning Disabilities</B></A>,  <B>The Emily Hall Tremaine Foundation </B>- This brochure is part of an  eight part information kit on learning disabilities. It includes general  information for teachers of LD students and gives suggestions for better  teaching strategies and techniques.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><MENU>  <P><A HREF="understanding_textbooks.html"><B>Improving Students' Understanding  Of Textbook Content</B></A><B>,</B> <B>LD OnLine Exclusive</B> article  by <B>Barbara Flanagan, M.S.</B>, gives both special and general educators  a new set of practices to utilize so that students with reading disabilities  can be more effectively involved in textbook learning.  <P><A HREF="study_skill_instruction.html"><B>A Call for More Study Skills  Instruction</B></A><B>, Joan Sedita, M.Ed., Director of Landmark Outreach  Training Program</B>- This useful article describes why LD students need  study skills instruction and presents an overview of the Landmark Study  Skills Model.  <P><A HREF="teaching-2.html"><B>Classroom Accommodations</B></A><B>, Parent  Journal,<I> </I>Spring 1996, Parents' Educational Resource Center- </B>This  is a list of accommodations that can be made for special students in the  classroom, as designated by Section 504. It includes suggestions for instruction,  testing, grades, homework, physical arrangement of the classroom and communication.  <BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="eric_digest539.html">Academic Interventions for Children with  Dyslexia who have Phonological Core Deficits</A>, ERIC Digest 539, 1995  - </B>A short summary of phonological core deficits, their impact on beginning  reading, identification, and interventions. Additional resources are also  provided.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="../reading/ltr-cec/ltr4-cec.html">Learning to Read...Reading  to Learn, Helping Children with Learning Disabilities To Succeed</A>, The  National Center to Improve the Tools of Educators, 1996 - </B>Tips for  teachers.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="../add_adhd/add-school1.html">Attention Deficit Disorder: What  Teachers Should Know</A>, U.S. Department of Education, 1994 - </B>This  article is a good source of information for all teachers. It describes  ways in which teachers can work with ADD students effectively.  <P><A HREF="../self_esteem/impact_of_teachers.html"><B>The Impact of Teachers:  A Story of Indelible Memories and Self-Esteem</B></A><B>, Robert B. Brooks,  Ph.D., Their World 1992, National Center for Learning Disabilities </B>-  A thought- provoking article about the incredible impact teachers can have  on children's lives.</MENU><H3>Learn more about it:</H3><MENU>  <P><A HREF="../../finding_help/publications_help/teach_learn_pubs.html"><B>Our  selection of publications</B></A> on teaching and learning strategies will  provide more in-depth learning.</MENU><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT SIZE="3" WIDTH="540%" NOSHADE></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=-2>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT></BODY></HTML>
