IDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD></TR><TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP"><TD><A HREF="../../audio_clips/audio-clips.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/audio.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Audio Clips" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.capaccess.org/cgi-bin/ldonline/netforum/ldf/a/1"><IMG SRC="../../images/bulletin.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Bulletin Board" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../ld_store/LD-Store.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/store.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="LD Store" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.weta.capaccess.org/ldonline/ld_survey.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/talk.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Talk Back" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../kidzone/kidzone.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/kid.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Kid Zone"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE><BR><!-MENU Bar Ends Here> <BR><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="540" HEIGHT="3" VSPACE="0"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"><BR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Technology</H2><P><BR>Technology can often be the key to access for children, youth and adultswith learning disabilities. Whether in the classroom or workplace setting,technology can provide the vital difference. Here you'll find articles togive you a basic understanding of technology, guest articles on the subject,and links to an abundance of online resources.</P><H3><BR>For Starters:</H3><MENU>  <P><A HREF="poor_richard_article.html"><B>LD OnLine Exclusive!</B></A><B>  - Richard Wanderman of Poor Richard's Publishing</B> writes on the many  ways computer technology can assist the student with learning disabilities.  <BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="learning_behavior.html">Technology Assistance for Learning  and Behavior</A></B> - <B>Maggie Kyger, Technology Specialist</B> at <B>James  Madison University</B>, offers helpful hints on using the computer and  other multimedia technology to create learning opportunities for students  with learning and behavior disorders.  <P><A HREF="hoovers_selection.html"><B>Selection of Software for Children  with Learning Disabilities</B></A> - compiled by <B>Anne Hoover</B>, Director  of Tutoring Services, <B>Kingsbury Center</B>, Washington, D.C.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="ldafactsheet.html">Assistive Technology for Individuals with  Learning Disabilities - A Fact Sheet</A>, LDA Newsbriefs, Jan./Feb. 1995  - </B>A basic informational article on assistive technology and the corresponding  federal legislation.<BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="perc_techtable.html">Technology and Learning Disabilities</A>  - Parents' Educational Resource Center, </B>Handout 7, June, 1994 <B>-  </B>This one page handout displays the programs that may help learning  disabled children better handle the challenges they face in reading, writing,  spelling, and other aspects of learning. <BR>  <BR>  <B><A HREF="at-iep.html">Facts About Assistive Technology and the IEP</A>  </B>- This short list of considerations is helpful when preparing the Individual  Education Program (IEP) for a student with learning disabilities. <BR>  </MENU><H3>Learn more about it:</H3><MENU>  <P><A HREF="../../finding_help/online_help/online-help.html#anchor666513"><B>Technology  Resources OnLine</B> </A>- A complete listing of technology resources for  parents and educators.</MENU><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT SIZE="3" WIDTH="540%" NOSHADE></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=-2>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT></BODY></HTML>
