<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Symposium Fact Sheet</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><!- Page designed and coded by Gene Cowan> <!-MENU Bar Starts Here> <BR><BR><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/main.gif" ALIGN="LEFT"WIDTH="75" HEIGHT="43" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 BORDER="0" ALT="Main Menu" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> <TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0> <TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD> <A HREF="../../whats_new/new.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/new.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 BORDER="0" ALT="What's New"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="../../abcs_info/articles-info.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/abc.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0BORDER="0" ALT="ABCs" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="../../ld_indepth/resource-guide.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/indepth.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0VSPACE=0 BORDER="0" ALT="In-Depth" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="../../finding_help/help.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/help.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0BORDER="0" ALT="Getting Help" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="../../ld_calendar/ld-calendar.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/calendar.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0VSPACE=0 BORDER="0" ALT="Calendar" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> </TR><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD> <IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="LEFT"WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"> </TD> <TD><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE=0VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"> </TD> <TD> <IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD> <TD> <IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"> </TD> <TD> <IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD> </TR> <TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD> <A HREF="../../audio_clips/audio-clips.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/audio.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0BORDER="0" ALT="Audio Clips" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="http://www.capaccess.org/cgi-bin/ldonline/netforum/ldf/a/1"><IMG SRC="../../images/bulletin.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0VSPACE=0 BORDER="0" ALT="Bulletin Board" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD><TD> <A HREF="../../ld_store/LD-Store.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/store.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0 BORDER="0" ALT="LD Store"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="http://www.weta.capaccess.org/ldonline/ld_survey.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/talk.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0BORDER="0" ALT="Talk Back" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> <TD> <A HREF="../../kidzone/kidzone.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/kid.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0BORDER="0" ALT="Kid Zone" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A> </TD> </TR> </TABLE><BR><BR><BR><!-MENU Bar Ends Here> <BR> <H2><CENTER><BR>Bringing out the Best in Our Children</CENTER></H2><H3><CENTER>by Charles R. Schwab<BR><BR></CENTER></H3>A recent Roper Poll reveals that a vast majority of Americans, includingparents, teachers and clinicians, do not understand the nature of learningproblems in children. Yet studies from Yale University have determined that20% of our children suffer from these problems. In San Francisco alone,this means that of the 100,000 children in our schools, 20,000 are strugglingto learn.<BR><BR>This does not come as a surprise to our teachers, who are confronted bythese problems in the classroom everyday and often do not have the toolsthey need to reach students who are failing. Teachers need to have accessto the latest teaching techniques and strategies just as much as our physiciansneed to be up to speed on the latest medical practices and breakthroughs.<BR><BR>In 1987, my wife, Helen, and I founded the Parents' Educational ResourceCenter, which provides information and resources to parents and professionalsseeking to help students with learning differences. PERC grew out of ourfamily's own experiences trying to find help for our son who was diagnosedwith dyslexia -- a reading problem he inherited from me.<BR><BR>From October 23-28, the Parents' Educational Resource Center will collaboratewith Dr. Mel Levine, one of the nation's foremost authorities on how childrenlearn, to present In the Way of Learning, four days of professional developmentand community education for over 10,000 Bay Area teachers, parents and clinicians.These symposia are a starting point to equip each of us with the informationwe need to help students with learning differences succeed in school.<BR><BR>More than 7,000 San Francisco teachers and administrators will participatein professional development that will help them to be more effective inrecognizing learning differences and employing strategies that enable academicprogress of students at all levels of ability. The San Francisco UnifiedSchool District, the San Francisco Office of Catholic Schools and the BayArea Independent School Heads Association have been instrumental in coordinatingthis unprecedented training opportunity.<BR><BR>According to the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development,&quot;less than 10 percent of our nation's teachers are adequately preparedto address learning deficits in their classrooms in a timely manner. Althoughwe now have the ability to identify and help at-risk youngsters as earlyas kindergarten, the majority of children with learning disabilities arenot identified until nine years of age.&quot; The research also indicatesthat for at least three-quarters of these children nine years old is toolate, intensifying school drop-out, illiteracy and juvenile delinquency.<BR><BR>This is underscored in a report issued by the National Commission on Teachingand America's Future which advocates for expanded training for teachersin child development, learning and teaching methods. And in a new reportissued by the Packard Foundation's Center for the Future of Children, whichcalls for &quot;intensive training of teachers&quot; in order to enableregular education teachers to meet the growing demands of children witha wide range of learning differences.<BR><BR>As a person who has struggled with reading problems all of my life, I believethat people who learn differently look at the world from unique perspectives.Many of our students are highly creative, visualizing solutions that mightnot occur to the rest of us. By identifying what gets in the way of learningfor students, we are able to nurture their strengths, improve their self-esteemand teach them the skills they will need to become our next inventors, leadersand entrepreneurs. As parents, clinicians and teachers, we have the opportunityto positively change a child's life. In the Way of Learning is designedto begin to teach us how, and to create a model that other school districtsaround the country can emulate to ensure that every child experiences authenticsuccess in both school and life.<BR><BR>An In The Way of Learning community presentation entitled &quot;Paying Attentionto Children's Attention&quot; will be held at the Masonic Auditorium onSaturday, October 26. Tickets are $25; waivers are available for those whocan not afford tickets. Call 415/655-2418.<BR><BR><BR><BR><HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="540%" ALIGN="LEFT" NOSHADE><BR><P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT> </CENTER></BODY></HTML>
