ome his speaking difficultiesby reading from a written script. Today he is known as the sonorous voiceof CNN and Bell-Atlantic, as well as for his many film roles, includingField of Dreams.</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><IMG SRC="../images/Dan%20O%27Brian.GIF" WIDTH="124" HEIGHT="180" ALIGN="LEFT" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>Overcoming obstacles, literally and figuratively, is what Olympic athleteDan O'Brien does best. The 1996 gold-medalist in the decathlon, O'Brienwas diagnosed just four years ago with ADD--Attention Deficit Disorder.Finally, he says, &quot;I understood why I had trouble in school.&quot;O'Brien channeled his abundant energy into sports, and despite his devastatingmisses at the Olympic trials in 1992, he was able to come back this yearand win. &quot;So many people fail and quit,&quot; he says. &quot;Well,it's OK to fail as long as you don't give up.&quot;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><IMG SRC="../images/Robert%20Nixon.GIF" WIDTH="169" HEIGHT="180" ALIGN="LEFT" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>Also honored for his achievements will be Washingtonian Robert H. Nixon,a celebrated conservationist and award-winning film maker. Nixon, who co-producedthe movie &quot;Gorillas in the Mist,&quot; which chronicles the work anddeath of anthropologist Dian Fossey, suffered with learning disabilitiesthat turned school into &quot;the most painful, threatening experience imaginable.Nature and the outdoors saved me. That's what I'm trying to pass on.&quot;As executive director of the Earth Conservation Corps, Nixon now helps disadvantagedyouths by putting them to work in the service of the environment.</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><IMG SRC="../images/Nell%20Minow.GIF" WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="180" ALIGN="LEFT" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></P><P>The fourth honoree at the gala is Washington native Nell Minow, a lawyer,author, mother, activist, and community leader. Minow is a principal partnerin the DC-based company Lens, Inc., an $80 million private investment fundthat buys stock in underperforming companies and uses shareholder activismto increase their value. She has co-authored three books on corporate responsibility,serves on the board of WETA, and is a frequent guest on CNN's Crossfire,Moneyline, and PBS's On The Issues. She has accomplished this and much moredespite learning disabilities that include severe directional impairmentand no visual memory. Labeled unmotivated as a student, Minow found it &quot;animmense relief to discover that my school problems were related to a learningdisability. I wish my teachers, my family, and I had had access to the kindof help available at The Lab School.&quot;</P><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>&nbsp;</H3><P>The Lab School of Washington, located in Washington, DC, provides a uniqueeducational opportunity for children with severe learning disabilities whoare not able to achieve academically in regular classrooms. The Lab Schooloffer individualized instruction and employs the use of multiple art formsin order to enhance the academic success of students. Graduates of the LabSchool of Washington include professionals in diverse fields such as art,engineering, business, theater, law and computer programming.</P><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Listen to Lab School Director, Sally Smith, talking about...</H3><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../audio_clips/smith-4.ram"><B>Learning disabledstudents and the support they need</B></A><B> </B>(47 seconds)</P><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../audio_clips/smith-1.ram"><B>The importance ofteaching organization</B></A><B> </B>(1.28 minutes)</P><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../audio_clips/smith-3.ram"><B>Teaching with Clubs</B></A>(52 seconds)<BR></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Discover more about <A HREF="http://www.labschool.org/">TheLab School of Washington</A></B></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><BR><HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="540%" NOSHADE></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=-2>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT></BODY></HTML>
