bar.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="3" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD></TR><TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP"><TD><A HREF="../../audio_clips/audio-clips.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/audio.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Audio Clips" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.capaccess.org/cgi-bin/ldonline/netforum/ldf/a/1"><IMG SRC="../../images/bulletin.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0"VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Bulletin Board" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../ld_store/LD-Store.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/store.gif"ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="LD Store" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.weta.capaccess.org/ldonline/ld_survey.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/talk.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Talk Back" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="../../kidzone/kidzone.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/kid.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="20" HSPACE="0" VSPACE="0" BORDER="0" ALT="Kid Zone"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE><BR><!-MENU Bar Ends Here> <BR><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="540" HEIGHT="3" VSPACE="0"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>A Selection of Gift Software for <BR> Children with Learning Disabilities</H2><P ALIGN=CENTER> <B>Anne Hoover<BR>The Kingsbury Center<BR>2138 Bancroft Place, N.W.<BR>Washington, DC 20008<BR></B></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Kid Phonics 1 CD</FONT> and <FONT SIZE=+1>KidPhonics 2 CD</FONT><BR>Davidson<BR>Ages 5 and up</B></P><P>Kid Phonics is excellent for children who need to practice hearing soundsand matching them to letters in a game format.  This program does a goodjob of providing extra drill and practice in phonics.    <BR></P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Kid Keys</FONT><BR>Davidson<BR>Ages 6 and up</B></P><P>This program is on floppy disk and may be hard to find, but it is wellworth the effort for a young child who needs to learn keyboarding.  It teachesbasic typing in a multisensory method and gives practice based on the alphabetsequence.<BR></P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>The Writing Center</FONT>, Ages 7 through12<BR><FONT SIZE=+1>The Student Writing Center</FONT>, Ages 10 and up<BR>The Learning Company</B></P><P>This is an excellent word processor for children and is used in manyarea schools.  In addition, it is easy to use.  Most children find it idealfor doing homework and writing projects. <BR></P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Kid Works Deluxe CD</FONT><BR>Davidson<BR>Ages 4 though 10</B></P><P>This program is a great way to encourage children to create stories!Children can use words, clip art, and pictures in place of words to writea story or make and print a book.   One of the special features of thisprogram is that the computer can read what the child has written.<BR></P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Imagination Express</FONT> Series<BR>Choose from Ocean, Rain Forest, Castle, Neighborhood,  Time Trip, USA, Pyramid<BR>Edmark<BR>Ages 6 through 12</B></P><P>Children love to spend hours creating scenes in their special  areasof interest using these programs.  Once the scene is set, the children havespace on the page to write about the picture they have created.  Many childrenfind starting with a visual picture helps them with written language. <BR></P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>The Graph Club</FONT><BR>Tom Snyder Productions<BR>Ages 6 throug12</B></P><P>This is a program that will appeal to children without seeming like itis math.  The Graph Club introduces children to sorting and classifyinginformation while encouraging problem solving.<BR></P><P><IMG SRC="../../images/violet.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Hollywood</FONT> and <FONT SIZE=+1>HollywoodHigh</FONT><BR>Theatrix<BR>Ages 9 and up</B></P><P>Students get so excited and involved in this program that it is hardto get them to stop.  Adults are just as intrigued.  The students get towrite and direct a play or movie by choosing characters, a set, animation,music, etc. The actual writing of the script becomes painless in this programwhich is sure to be a hit with creative children.</P><P ALIGN=CENTER><HR WIDTH="75%"></P><P ALIGN=CENTER>The Kingsbury Center is a nonprofit educational organizationthat provides comprehensive services to support children and adults withlearning disabilities through its Tutoring Services, <BR>Assessment Services and Kingsbury Day School.  <BR>e-mail: KNGSBRYCTR@AOL.COM<BR><BR>Our thanks to Anne Hoover for compiling this software listing for <B>LDOnLine</B>!</P><P ALIGN=CENTER><BR><HR SIZE="3" NOSHADE><BR><FONT SIZE=-2>&copy;1996 WETA</FONT></BODY></HTML>
