VSPACE=0 NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"><P>
<H2><CENTER>Learning Disorders and the Flow of Expectations</CENTER>
</H2>
<P><CENTER>Melvin D. Levine, M.D., F.A.A.P.<BR>
<BR>
<B>NATIONAL CENTER FOR LEARNING DISABILITIES<BR>
<BR>
</B>Their World Magazine<BR>
1990<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P><A NAME="anchor162723"></A><B>Table of Contents:<BR>
<BR>
I.</B> <B><A HREF="#anchor866605">Evolving Expectations</A></B><BR>
<B>A.</B> <A HREF="#anchor866191">Language</A><BR>
<B>B.</B> <A HREF="#anchor865183">Memory</A><BR>
<B>C.</B> <A HREF="#anchor864434">Attention</A><BR>
<B>D.</B> <A HREF="#anchor863987">Fine Motor Skills</A><BR>
<B>E.</B> <A HREF="#anchor863614">Thinking Skills</A><BR>
<BR>
<B>II.</B> <B><A HREF="#anchor863094">Some Implications</A></B><BR>
<BR>
<B>III.</B> <B><A HREF="#anchor862342">Reason for Optimism</A></B><BR>
<BR>
<B>IV.</B> <B><A HREF="#anchor861851">What to Look For: Some First Signs
of Trouble Keeping Up with the Flow of Expectations<BR>
</A></B><BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H5>EDITOR'S NOTE: This comprehensive feature describing learning disabilities
has been written for parents who read <I>Their World</I>. We suggest that
you use it for ongoing reference as your LD child goes through different
developmental stages. Dr. Melvin Levine is Professor of Pediatrics, School
of Medicine and Director of The Clinical Center for the Study of Development
and Learning, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, North Carolina.
He is a member of the National Center for Learning Disabilities Professional
Advisory Board.</H5>
<BR>
Children with learning disorders find themselves immersed in a perpetually
changing flow of expectations. In a sense, a child's developing nervous
system navigating against &quot;a relentless stream of evolving demands.&quot;
Consequently, the nature and impacts of relevant disabilities are likely
to change over time. Such change has critical implications for the evaluation,
education, and overall outlook of children with learning disorders. 
<H4><A NAME="anchor866605"></A>EVOLVING EXPECTATIONS</H4>
As children progress through the school years, it is anticipated that there
will be steady improvement in all basic abilities. Academic demands are
based on the assumption that students will show progressively greater accuracy,
speed, and flexibility in language, memory, spatial awareness, motor skills,
concentration. and reasoning. When slow or inadequate development occurs
in one or more of these functions, an ever widening gap in academic skill
and performance is likely to ensue. <BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents</A></B><BR>
<H4><A NAME="anchor866191"></A>LANGUAGE</H4>
Language is one function that must keep pace with rapidly evolving expectation
in school. Initially when they are enrolled in school, children discover
vast differences between verbal communication at home and the literate language
of the classroom. At home much of what is said is predictable, redundant,
and tightly bound to contexts. When Sour neither gains access to your messy
bedroom, you don't have to be a proficient linguist to comprehend that she
is saying' The context determines the message. Parents regulate the speed
and complexity of their verbal utterances to meet the processing capabilities
of their child. In school, language is much less redundant, it occurs in
larger chunks (i.e., longer sentences containing more ideas and demandhig
sustained listening), and the rate of communication is seldom customized
to satisfy the needs of an individual listener. The teacher must calibrate
the rate and complexity of her language to match the capacities of the average
student.<BR>
<BR>
Progressively and insidiously language demands grow. Verbally presented
material becomes increasingly abstract and decontextualized (less bound
to What is happening here and now). At the same time, children must become
increasingly effective at expressing complex ideas through language and
at doing so rather quickly and efficiently (in case they are called upon
in class).<BR>
<BR>
Language increasingiv intrudes in all academic skills. During the early
grades, while children are acquiring basic decoding skills for reading,
they need to have a good sense of phonology or language sounds. Once they
are able to master such sounds, associate them with visual symbols, and
tease them out and recombine them to form words, they have overcome the
decoding barrier. They need to become adept with syntax or word order, so
that they can derive meaning from complex sentences in texts. In third and
fourth grade, the language sophistication of reading a book is generally
less sophisticated than the language of everyday conversation. In fourth
grade such language reaches a higher level, but much of what a child reads
confirms what he or she already knew. By fifth grade, students are reading
to acquire new knowledge; there is a much higher density of ideas, facts,
and new vocabulary cloaked in difficult syntax. Concurrently, language becomes
increasingly critical as a medium for writing; students are expected to
become adept at the verbal encoding of ideas on paper. Even mathematics
requires considerable language sophistication, as children need to be able
to process verbal explanations of difficult mathematical procedures. Language
also becomes an increasing challenge as students undertake the solution
of word problems. Finally, language facility is taxed most heavily when
it is time to master a second language; many children with underlying language
dysfunctions have serious problems meeting this lofty expectation.<BR>
<BR>
The turbulent flow of language demands clearly takes its toll on children
who are verbally vulnerable. Youngsters with language based learning disorders
may be delayed at acquiring basic decoding skills for reading. Affected
students may eventually acquire good decoding skills for reading, but they
may encounter difficulty with reading comprehension and, in particular,
with the ability to summarize, apply, or remember what they have read. As
language demands intensify, they may falter in following directions and
assimilating verbal explanations. Students with relatively mild language
difficulties may have little, if any, trouble during the early grades of
school but they then may experience a confusing gradual decline in performance
as the evolving expectations for competency in language begin to exceed
their current linguistic capacities. <BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B>
<H4><A NAME="anchor865183"></A>MEMORY</H4>
Heightened memory strain also becomes increasingly evident as students progress
through school. In the earliest grades, the ability to form one to one associations
in memory is critical. First and second graders must associate groups of
letters with English language sounds. Their minds must store numbers with
quantities, operational signs with specific arithmetic procedures, and words
with their definitions. Young students are also expected to be good at recognition;
they need to be able to distinguish between what they have encountered preciously
and what is new.<BR>
<BR>
The early stress on association and recognition memory abruptly gives way
to a compelling need for recall or retrieval memory in late elementary school,
at which time, students are expected to excavate sizable configurations
of knowledge and skill from memory. They must do so rapidly and with precision.
Often they need to recall several different things simultaneously. For example,
while writing an essay, a sixth grade student must simultaneously recall
spelling, punctuation, grammar, capitalization, letter formation, vocabulary,
the topic, prior factual knowledge, and new ideas. Such simultaneous memory
drainage may create serious problems for students who have not yet developed
sufficient retrieval memory facility. These students typically have enormous
difficulties writing in the middle grades. They frequently exhibit an embarrassing
discrepancy between the caliber of their thoughts when they speak and the
(very poor) quality of ideas they transmit on paper. Their writings may
be barely legible, highly inconsistent, disorganized, and replete with mechanical
errors. For them the process of writing is tedious, unrersarding, and often
an embarrassment.<BR>
<BR>
As students progress through school, memory demands continue to evolve.
There is a requirement for more cumulative recall or the ability to remember
late in the year what was learned in the fall. This form of memory is critical
in foreign languages and most science and mathematics courses. In order
to operate efficiently in these curricula, students also need to develop
keen insights into how memory works. Such astute memory is characteristic
of many successful learners. Those who have trouble keeping pace with evolving
memory demands commonly reveal little or no insight into the operation of
memory. Consequently, they usually possess no effective memory strategies.
They have no inkling of how to study for a test or engage in other techniques
to make memory work more easily and effectively for them.<BR>
<BR>
Over the school years memory must become increasingly automatized. Students
must do more than recall information and skill accurately; much of what
is known must be recalled effortlessly, with very little expenditure of
attention, and with incredible speed. Such automatic memory is crucial if
students are to superimpose highly sophisticated knowledge and skill over
prior learning. It is virtually impossible to write a perceptive and sensitive
book report when too much effort, attentional resource, or time must be
allocated to remembering how to form certain letters or to recalling rules
of punctuation. Similarly, a student is unlikely to become skilled in algebra
if she has to hesitate in recalling multiplication facts. <BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B>
<H4><A NAME="anchor864434"></A>ATTENTION</H4>
The demands on attention also intensify over time. Students need to focus
more and more selectively. When they read or listen, they must become increasingly
selective in determining what facts or concepts are most important and which
are less critical or relevant. As adolescents proceed through secondary
school, the level of distraction becomes a greater and greater threat to
concentration. Social distractions become particularly potent. Moreover,
in secondary school, there is a virtual explosion of detail in many content
area courses. Students who are tuning in and out erratically because they
have weak attention, are likely to miss critical inputs. In addition, many
adolescents with attention deficits have tremendous difficulty coping with
the memory demands of the secondary school curriculum. They seem to have
their greatest problems in courses that stress the systematic use of memory.
<BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B>
<H4><A NAME="anchor863987"></A>FINE MOTOR SKILLS</H4>
Fine motor skills also become stressed as students proceed through school.
The demand for large amounts of writing makes it necessary that children
have effective control over finger movements. They must be adept at integrating
fine motor output with memory, so they can master the extended and varied
motor patterns needed for cursive writing. The demand for motor memory becomes
pronounced as students progress through the late years of elementary school.
Some children are far more rapid and accurate in their thinking and language
skills than they are in their fine motor abilities, a disparity that commonly
creates serious problems when it comes to meeting expectations for large
volumes of written output. Their fingers just can't keep pace with their
minds! <BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B>
<H4><A NAME="anchor863614"></A>THINKING SKILLS</H4>
The curriculum in many content areas confronts children with more and more
challenging problem solving tasks and the need for increasingly abstract
conceptual thinking. During the early grades, students can rely heavily
on the rote recall of procedures to solve problems in mathematics and to
meet problem solving challenges in other realms as well. As they approach
and pass through secondary school, they need to have a keen understanding
of the problems they are solving. They need to be increasingly flexible,
planful, strategic, and attentive in their approach to such problems. Older
students also must acquire firm grasps on concepts. In the early grades,
most of the conceptual content of courses is concrete. There then ensues
a steady flow of new concepts that are less tangible. These include such
abstract notions as liberalism, democracy, proportion, and equation. Some
students have a great deal of difficulty becoming flexible problem solvers
and abstract conceptualizers. Their thinking becomes passive, rigid, concrete,
and overreliant on rote methods. Often they acquire only partial understanding
or tenuous grasps of abstract concepts. Further, they may be totally unaware
of how tenuous their grasps actually are! <BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B>
<H4><A NAME="anchor863094"></A>SOME IMPLICATIONS</H4>
It is clearly evident that as expectations evolve, the learning disorders
of childhood change in their precise manifestations. In some cases, a child
may not even display academic difficulties until the flow of evolving expectations
surpass her or his particular weak functions for the first time. For example,
a student destined to have trouble with simultaneous memory may not falter
until late elementary school when the demands for multipie recall in writing
and other domains become pronounced. A student with relatively mild language
problems may have little or no difficulty until he is required to master
a foreign language. A child may possess compensatory strengths that are
applicable at a certain point in their education but far less usable at
other educational stages. For example, a student with excellent visual perceptual
abilities and strengths in her visual memory may be able to compensate for
relatively deficient language abilities and develop a good sight vocabulary
for reading in the early grades. Unfortunately, visual perceptual strengths
are not highly rewarded in secondary school; that student's strong visualization
skills will do little to help her overcome her poor reading comprehension
in eleventh grade.<BR>
<BR>
Fortunately, there are instances where the flow of expectations can have
a healing effect. A student with certain deficiencies of memory may falter
academically during late elementary school then improve considerably because
she is excellent with abstract verbal concepts and is able to deploy such
ability as well as her clever problem solving strategies to overcome her
memory weaknesses. In this way, evolving expectations can actually make
certain students more resilient. The message is clear: Patterns of learning
difficulty change over time. They can change for the better or thev can
change for the worse. The lessons we can learn from an awareness of the
how of expectations include the following:<BR>
<BR>
1. Because of evolving expectations, a student can start to exhibit a learning
disorder at virtually any age or grade level.<BR>
<BR>
2. Because different brain functions change in their academic relevance
at different ages, the content of evaluations of students must relate to
the expectations of their specific age and grade levels. For example, schools
and clinics need to use several different testing procedures to uncover
relevant memory problems in a 14 year old from the ones needed to pinpoint
memory gaps in a 6 year old.<BR>
<BR>
3. Teachers must be keenly aware of the specific new cognitive demands that
their curricula are placing upon students. Teachers can be especially helpful
in identifying students who are struggling inordinately and who seem unable
to keep pace with new expectations.<BR>
<BR>
4. Parents and professionals working with children who have learning disorders
need to be able to anticipate difficulties that are likely to occur as a
result of the flow of expectations in the future. Such anticipation can
allow for adequate preparation of the student while targeted curriculum
modifications can be implementedwhen he lags too far behind or becomes too
demoralized.<BR>
<BR>
5. Future research into learning disorders needs to be developmentally oriented.
There needs to be recognition that the array of learning disorders of one
age group is likely to differ significantly from that of another. <BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B>
<H4><A NAME="anchor862342"></A>REASON FOR OPTIMISM</H4>
Children with learning disorders need to have a keen understanding of evolving
expectations and their impacts. But most of all they must come to realize
that expectations never stop flowing that then evolve on into adult life;
but that grown ups have the option of selecting most of their expectations.
Children are expected to be good at just about everything. In adulthood,
on the other hand, when you pursue a career you need primarily to strengthen
your strengths and select mainly a set of expectations that you feel confident
you can meet. So it is that students need to recognize the need to strengthen
their strengths and look ahead to a time in life when they will be free
to practice their specialties and successfully control or direct the flow
of expectations.<BR>
<BR>
Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B><BR>
<A NAME="anchor861851"></A><B>WHAT TO LOOK FOR:</B> SOME FIRST SIGNS OF
TROUBLE KEEPING UP WITH THE FLOW OF EXPECTATIONS<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE><TABLE border=1 cellspacing=5 cellpadding=5> <TR><TD></TD><TD><B>Language</B></TD><TD><B>Memory</B></TD><TD><B>Attention</B></TD><TD><B>Fine
Motor Skill</B></TD><TD><B>Other Functions</B></TD></TR> <TR><TD><B>Preschool</B></TD><TD>Pronunciation
problems<BR>
<BR>
Slow vocabulary growth<BR>
<BR>
Lack of interest in story telling<BR>
<BR>
</TD><TD>Trouble learning number, alphabet, days of week, etc.<BR>
<BR>
Poor memory for routines<BR>
<BR>
</TD><TD>Trouble sitting still<BR>
<BR>
Extreme restlessness<BR>
<BR>
Impersistence at tasks<BR>
<BR>
</TD><TD>Trouble learning self help skills (e.g. tying shoe laces)<BR>
<BR>
Clumsiness<BR>
<BR>
Reluctance to draw or trace<BR>
<BR>
</TD><TD>Trouble learning left from right (possible visual spatial confusion)<BR>
<BR>
Trouble interacting (weak social skills)<BR>
<BR>
</TD></TR> <TR><TD><B>Lower Grades</B></TD></TR> <TR><TD><B>Middle Grades</B></TD></TR><TR><TD><B>Upper
Grades</B></TD></TR> </TABLE>

Back to the <B><A HREF="#anchor162723">Table of Contents<BR>
</A></B><BR>
Melvin D. Levine, M.D. F.A.A.P.<BR>
<I>THEIR WORLD </I>'90 published by the National Center for Learning Disabilties.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

