<H2><CENTER>Questions To Ask When Having Your Child Assessed </CENTER>
</H2>
<P><CENTER><BR>
<B>PARENTS' EDUCATIONAL RESOURCE CENTER<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P><B>Family Questions</B> 
<UL>
  <LI>Why do I want an assessment for my child? 
  <LI>What should be included in the assessment? 
  <LI>What qualifications do I want the professional who is doing the testing
to have? 
  <LI>How should I prepare my child for the assessment? 
</UL>
<BR>
<B>Assessment Question</B> 
<UL>
  <LI>What credentials/training have you had in educational testing? 
  <LI>What experience have you had with testing students my child's age?
  <LI>Before the assessment, can I have a written plan of what you will
do and what the results will tell me? 
  <LI>Will the assessment include all of the tests required by public schools
so that my child will be considered for receiving services? 
  <LI>What can I expect in terms of a written report at the end of the assessment?
  <LI>Will the final report integrate all of the individual tests done?
  <LI>How long have you been doing assessments? 
  <LI>How much will the assessment cost? 
</UL>
<BR>
<B>Follow-up Questions</B> 
<UL>
  <LI>Were the assessment report results clear? If not, was the professional
able to answer all of my questions? 
  <LI>What did the professional recommend for my child based on these test
results? 
</UL>
<HR>From the Parents' Educational Resource Center (PERC), a program of the
Charles and Helen Schwab Foundation. <BR>
&nbsp; <BR>

